<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 31 日星期一 12:10:01 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Dear Therapist: My Husband Had a Relationship With His Best Friend]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>他所说的这个对他来说“像兄弟一样”的人，事实证明他的意义远不止于此。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Gjv56aDhFbpjwlv5rI1BK1uXHms=/0x0:4950x2784/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/My_Husband_Used_to_Sleep_With_His_Male_Best_Friend_final/original.jpg" alt="一幅丈夫和妻子躺在床上的插图，一个像植物一样的人拥抱着丈夫。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>比安卡·巴格纳雷利插图</figcaption></figure><strong>亲爱的治疗师，</strong><br><br>我和我丈夫结婚一年了，在此之前我们约会了三年。他与前妻结婚20多年，育有一个孩子。在他第一次结婚之前，我听说过他的许多前女友，而且我知道他在婚姻结束后、和我约会之前有过一个女朋友。<br><br>他还有一个最好的朋友，一个住在我们隔壁的人。我们婚礼几周后，我在文件柜里找地方存放我从以前家带来的一些文件，我看到一张纸卡在滚轮里。上面写着“[他最好朋友的名字]喜欢[我丈夫的名字]。”我想知道这是怎么回事，所以我侵犯了他的隐私。我发现了这位朋友写给我丈夫的许多卡片和情书，日期是我们结婚前 12 年左右。<br><br>我哭了，很震惊。我和我的丈夫交谈，他说，在与结婚二十年的妻子离婚后，他很受伤。他想要的不是女人，而是一个伴侣。我发现他在那段时间（大约四年）与几个男人交谈过，直到他努力克服自己的感情。他让他最好的朋友搬出了他的房子，但那个朋友仍然住在我们隔壁，在我丈夫家的财产上。我必须每天都被提醒他们之间发生的事情。他们在一起时发生了性关系，现在当我看着他们两个时，这就是我所能想象的。<br><br>我知道我进入这个圈子已经过去了大约十年，但我很痛苦。我丈夫说他对他的朋友不再有任何浪漫的感觉了。我丈夫是独生子，他说这个最好的朋友就像兄弟一样。<br><br>这一切都让我很烦恼。距离我知道已经一年多了，我似乎仍然无法接受我的丈夫。我能做些什么来克服这个问题？我的丈夫对每个人都充满爱心和友善。他对我和我的女儿很好，并且热爱他和我的家人。但我一直看到他过去的错误。他说那是他的过去，发生在我出现之前。尽管如此，每天被提醒还是很困难。<br><br><strong>匿名的</strong><br><br><strong>亲爱的匿名者，</strong><br><br>一段关系中最令人不安的经历之一就是发现某些事情并不像看上去的那样。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/02/how-to-tell-child-sperm-donor/673194/">秘密的发现</a>会让你重新评估你自以为了解的关于伴侣的一切，并让你质疑你的现实感和你自以为共同的信任。<br><br>对你来说，还有一个额外的层面，即两个秘密同时被揭露。首先，你丈夫最亲密的朋友也是他的前任。其次，你的丈夫曾与男性发生过关系。尽管这两个事实都让你感到困惑和被背叛，但对你来说，单独考虑你对这些发现的反应很重要，以便找出如何继续前进并从这些欺骗中治愈。<br><br>关于第一点，你的丈夫与你只认识他最好的朋友的人有一段浪漫的关系，而你却因疏忽的谎言而感到震惊。暂时把性别放在一边（因为我们接下来会讨论这个问题），你没有被告知某个与他非常亲近并且作为你的隔壁邻居出现在你的生活中的人与你的丈夫有性史。这并不是“哎呀，我忘了提及”的疏忽，而是故意阻止您发现。我说性别不是这里的问题，因为即使这个人是女性，我想如果你没有被告知他最亲密的朋友（也住在你的共同财产上）也是他的前任，你也会感到被背叛。<br><br>当你的信任被破坏后，你感到痛苦是有道理的。尽管你们就自己的发现进行了交谈，并且您的丈夫也坦白了自己的历史，但仍需要采取更多措施来修复他的不诚实造成的损害。例如，他有没有告诉过你为什么他没有告诉你他和他最好的朋友的恋情，以及他将来会采取什么措施来诚实？无论出于何种原因，他是否对隐瞒此事承担全部责任？ （“是的，我撒谎了，但这是因为 X”和“我因为 X 撒了谎，但无论如何，我不应该撒谎，我承诺将来对你诚实”之间是有区别的。 ) 你有没有与他分享过，当你们一起开始婚姻时，他对这个秘密的掌握让你感觉如何不受束缚，以及你对未来的诚实期望是什么？<br><br>当你们进行这样的谈话时，你需要带着好奇和同情心来倾听，这并不意味着你不追究他欺骗你的责任。相反，您正在创建一个可以在你们之间培养更多信任的环境。例如，他可能会说他不敢告诉你，因为他相信你会因为前任每天的出现而感到威胁，并希望他结束一段对他来说非常重要的友谊，而他感到在披露和失去他之间陷入了困境。最好的朋友。他可能会说他担心如果你知道他被男人吸引，你可能会拒绝他甚至离开他（考虑到你的反应，他可能是对的）。反过来，你可能会告诉他，他隐藏了与他经常互动的前任的相关信息，这让你想知道他还可能隐藏了什么，并质疑你是否可以信任他：他是否分享了他们过去和现在的全部情况关系？难道他还隐藏着其他与这个人无关的秘密？<br><br>当你说话时，确保你不仅对他完全诚实，而且对你自己也完全诚实。你需要反思什么能让你在未来几年感到安全，并将其传达给他。这可能包括对他与他最好的朋友的关系进行全面的说明，以便以后故事的更多方面不会被泄露，他现在与您分享任何明显的遗漏谎言，这样就不会再出现任何意外（您可以将此描述为“如果有什么我想知道的，现在是时候告诉我了，因为稍后告诉我可能会让我无法再次信任你或和你在一起”），并进行夫妻治疗来共同解决这个问题。这些只是建议——你必须决定你真正需要什么，并提出要求。<br><br>您还可以讨论您对当前生活安排的感受。如果一开始就没有秘密，这可能不是问题，但现在可能会成为问题，因为你的信任已经破裂。也许你对他们持续的友谊感到满意，但希望前任不住在隔壁，或者考虑到他们恋爱多久了，你可能对这种接近感到满意。当您回答这个问题时，需要考虑一下当您说“每天都想起”您丈夫的前任很难时，您的意思是什么。哪一个提醒对你来说是困难的：他和你生活中的前任有过一段浪漫的过去，他为此欺骗了你，或者前任是个男人？<br><br>这让我想到了第二个秘密——你丈夫对男人的吸引力——这对你们俩来说似乎都更复杂。你和你的丈夫似乎都对自己的性取向感到不舒服。在与前任约会并与几个男人交谈了四年之后，你说“他努力克服自己的感情”，这表明他感到羞耻或否认，而你的不赞成和判断在你称他与一个男人约会时表现出来“他过去的错误”——这是你不会对他的任何前女友说的话。你们似乎都不愿意承认你的丈夫对男人和女人都有吸引力，你需要检查你丈夫的性取向会给你们俩带来什么，这样这些感觉就不会导致更多的秘密。<br><br>您可以首先探索为什么您“似乎无法接受”他，并澄清您对双性恋的任何误解或假设。也许你认为这意味着他将永远怀念与男人在一起的时光，因此可能会欺骗你——这不是性吸引力的运作方式。正如你总是会被其他人所吸引一样，他也会如此；关键是，如果你们都选择一夫一妻制的关系，你们都不会按照这些愿望行事。你可以请他与你分享他作为一个同时被男人和女人吸引的人的经历，以便他能够澄清他的性取向对他意味着什么。你可以谈论你们各自的历史，以及关于同性伙伴关系的文化或家庭耻辱，以及这些观点如何演变，以便你的丈夫有空间被你充分地爱着他真实的自我——一个似乎被吸引的男人男性和女性，以及一夫一妻制婚姻。如果你强迫他隐藏真实的自我，你就会鼓励他更多地保守秘密，并使你的丈夫为自己的身份感到羞耻。你可能需要花一些时间试图理解（也许在治疗师的帮助下）你所爱并被吸引的男人是如何在你的脑海中变成另一个人的——一个你厌恶的人——因为他有过一段与他交往的历史。与他同性别的伴侣。<br><br>有时我们不会谈论我们最需要讨论的事情，因为一旦承认事实，我们就无法不承认它。现在，你们俩的表现就好像你们的丈夫对男人不感兴趣，甚至在他与男人发生性关系时也没有（相反，你写道他在离婚的过程中想要“一个伴侣”）。如果你想要一段基于诚实的婚姻，回避真相是没有帮助的。<br><br>事实是这样的：你丈夫的浪漫过去是他的一部分，就像你的过去是你的一部分一样。我们都希望在婚姻中展现出完整的自我，并因为真实的自己而被爱和接受。既然秘密已经公开，不要否认它们对你所结婚的人意味着什么，而是一起拥抱真相，尽管它的复杂性和不适性，这样你就可以以你所渴望的信任和开放来建立这段新的婚姻。<br><br> <em>《亲爱的治疗师》仅供参考，不构成医疗建议，也不能替代专业的医疗建议、诊断或治疗。如果您对健康状况有任何疑问，请务必寻求您的医生、心理健康专家或其他合格的医疗服务提供者的建议。提交信件即表示您同意</em>《大西洋月刊<em>》使用该信件的部分或全部内容，我们可能会对其长度和/或清晰度进行编辑。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/husband-best-friend-relationship-advice-trust/674858/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/husband-best-friend-relationship-advice-trust/674858/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Show That Knows the Secret to Serialized TV]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Yair Rosenberg 的娱乐必备<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1IJm7MhDj5qxKLJ7SjLICWbQ9bA=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/babylon_5/original.jpg" alt="巴比伦5号空间站图片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>华纳兄弟。</figcaption></figure><small><i data-stringify-type="italic">这是</i>《大西洋<i data-stringify-type="italic">日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br>欢迎回到《每日邮报》的周日文化版，一位<i>大西洋月刊的</i>作家在其中揭示了是什么让他们开心。<br><br>今天的特邀嘉宾是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>特约撰稿人亚伊尔·罗森伯格。 Yair 撰写有关政治、文化和宗教交集的文章，也是我们的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/">Deep Shtetl</a>时事通讯的作者。他最近揭示了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-supreme-court-netanyahu-parliament/674833/">以色列社会信任崩溃的情况</a>，提供了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/">建立更好的社交媒体平台</a>的路线图， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/6494bbb2a1d6420038c5cb21/congress-antisemitism-yair-rosenberg/">在国会就反犹太主义作证</a>，并与演员本普拉特谈论了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/641c6dfed18ff80037f5eb02/ben-platt-parade-interview-yair-rosenberg-jews/">犹太教在表演者作品中所扮演的角色。百老汇</a>。亚尔目前正在创作一本独特的科幻短篇小说集，尽管给洋基队带来了巨大的痛苦，但仍为洋基队加油，并回忆了一项已不复存在的神奇科技。<br><br>首先，这是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的三篇周日读物：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/sound-of-freedom-qanon-culture-war/674832/">“我看了‘他们’不想让你看的电影。”</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/">芭比就是一切。肯就是其他一切。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/sinead-oconnor-legacy-mandinka-song/674844/">这首歌曲首次俘获了西妮德·奥康纳的力量</a></li><b>文化调查：Yair Rosenberg</b><br><br><b>我十几岁时就喜欢的一种文化产品：</b>在高中时，我最珍贵的财产之一是便携式 DVD 播放器。这正是它听起来的样子：带有屏幕的翻盖设备，可以播放光盘上的电影。拥有一台意味着我可以在学校越野旅行时观看<i>《指环王》</i> ，或者躲在自己的房间里狂看 Netflix 的电视节目（那时他们还给你寄 DVD）。我费了好大劲才说服父母帮我拿到那东西，以前我去哪儿都带着它。如今，便携式播放器已成为博物馆藏品，早已被功能更强大、播放更高质量视频的智能手机所取代。但再多的处理能力或像素分辨率也无法取代公交车上那个可以点播电影的怪孩子的魔力。<br><br><b>我最近重新观看、重读或以其他方式重温的东西：</b>我最喜欢的电视节目之一是一部古怪的 90 年代科幻传奇，名为<i>《巴比伦 5》</i> 。该剧的独特之处在于其创作者 J. Michael Straczynski 提前规划了整个五年的故事情节。他基本上写了整部小说，然后将其搬上银幕。正如我为<i>《大西洋月刊》</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/harry-potter-hbo-reboot-tv-series-jk-rowling/673816/">所写的</a>那样，当今大多数连续剧电视节目都令我失望。他们的情节往往不会成功，因为编剧们都是边编边编。 <i>《迷失》</i>就是一个典型的例子，但还有很多其他例子。 <i>《巴比伦5》</i>则相反，它不断地预示事件——有时甚至提前整季——并带领角色踏上可信的成长、发现和悲剧之旅。我一直在重温这部剧，因为它很令人愉快，而且还因为斯特拉钦斯基将于下个月以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt27712788/">原创动画电影</a>的形式发布这个故事的新部分。<br><br><b>我最喜欢的大片和最喜欢的艺术电影：</b>我是那些不仅在前面提到的便携式 DVD 播放器上观看每部<i>《指环王》</i>电影的加长版，而且还与所有演员和工作人员一起观看多次的人之一评论。这就是我知道重要事情的方式，比如当布景设计师试图为角色在被洪水淹没的艾辛格堡垒中创造一条漂浮的苹果路径时，制作是如何暂时中断的，结果苹果拒绝漂浮。最终，他们意识到自己被设计完美的蜡制道具水果愚弄了。<br><br>我在聚会上很受欢迎。<br><br>至于艺术电影，这可能是一种作弊，但我会选择<i>脚注</i>。这是一部外语电影，所以从定义上来说并不是一部大片，但它确实赢得了以色列相当于奥斯卡奖的最佳影片奖，并且在 2012 年获得了真正的奥斯卡最佳外语片奖。正如我<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/6351cf31fb1fdd00362a68d8/guide-jewish-history-culture-anti-semitism/">在其他地方</a>所说的那样，“它是可以肯定地说，导演约瑟夫·锡达的<i>《脚注》</i>是您看过的唯一一部获得奥斯卡提名的关于塔木德学者的戏剧喜剧。这也是一部关于父子、代际冲突以及古往今来犹太文本激发的激情的非凡电影。”这部电影取材于现实生活中的一个学术王朝，其成员包括我自己的亲戚，这并没有什么坏处。 <b>[相关：</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/6351cf31fb1fdd00362a68d8/guide-jewish-history-culture-anti-semitism/">如何从犹太人而不是讨厌他们的人那里了解犹太人</a><b>]</b><br><br><b>我什么都会看的演员：</b>彼得·萨斯加德。他拥有令人难以置信的魅力和范围，无论是在《<i>破碎的玻璃》</i> （有史以来关于现代新闻业的最佳电影）中扮演一位顽强的杂志编辑，揭露他的一位明星记者的寓言，还是在<i>《教育》</i>中体现一个掠夺性但具有磁性的骗子艺术家，<i> </i>诱捕一位易受影响的大学生（由伟大的凯瑞·穆里根扮演）和她的家人。<br><br><b>我最近读过的最好的小说作品：</b>我一直在努力阅读一本新的科幻短篇小说选集，名为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/jewish-futures-science-fiction-from-the-world-s-oldest-diaspora-michael-a-burstein/9781515458050?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《犹太未来》</i></a> 。它将于下个月发布，但我在 Kickstarter 上支持了该项目，所以我得到了一份预发本。我迫不及待地想让其他人能够阅读它——不仅仅是因为我姐姐对此做出了贡献。与所有选集一样，不同的故事会向不同的读者讲述，但迄今为止我最喜欢的是 Leah Cypess 的搞笑《Frummer House》，讲述了当智能家居开始对其居民强加宗教仪式时会发生什么； 《The Ascent》是亚伯拉罕·约瑟芬·里斯曼 (Abraham Josephine Riesman) 和 SI·罗森鲍姆 (SI Rosenbaum) 创作的关于耶路撒冷永恒修复和毁灭的令人难忘的故事；当然，还有我姐姐 SM Rosenberg 的《月亮旋律》，它是米德拉什和超级英雄故事的结合体。<br><br><b>最后一个让我哭泣的文化或娱乐事件：</b>纽约洋基队的进攻，或者更确切地说，缺乏进攻。<br><br><b>我最近收到的一个很好的文化或娱乐建议：</b>停止观看洋基队。我没有听。<br><br><b>一位对我来说意义重大的音乐艺术家：</b>我喜欢爱尔兰民间音乐——它的合唱品质、它的代际吸引力、它反映和延续文化记忆的方式。我会听当代四重奏组 The High Kings 录制的任何歌曲。该乐队的所有四名成员都是多乐器演奏家，拥有令人难以置信的独特声音，以某种方式无缝地融入四声部和声。他们自 2008 年以来一直在创作音乐，他们的专长是通过忠实于原始精髓的现代编曲，将经典的爱尔兰吉格舞和民谣带给新的听众。当我不写作时，我的副业爱好是作曲、唱歌和录制犹太音乐，我的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://bit.ly/azyashir">第一张专辑</a>深受这种方法的影响，将传统的安息日歌曲与现代旋律和乐器结合起来。<br><br><b>我会读任何作品的作家：</b>石黑一雄，既因为他的写作毫不费力地优雅，也因为它奖励对道德主题的更深入思考。举个例子：我最近读了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-buried-giant-kazuo-ishiguro/9780307455796?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《被掩埋的巨人》</i></a> ，它让我进入了另一本书《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/forgiveness-an-alternative-account-matthew-ichihashi-potts/9780300259858?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>宽恕》</i></a> ，作者是哈佛大学纪念教堂的首席牧师马修·市桥·波茨（Matthew Ichihashi Potts），他使用了几部文学作品（包括石黑一雄的作品）来挑战传统观念宽恕并提供替代方法。 <b>[相关</b>： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/63399d48fb1fdd0036293c1e/yom-kippur-forgiveness-anti-semitism-antepli/">我最喜欢的反犹太主义者教给我关于宽恕的知识</a><b>]</b><br><br><b>我上一次关于文化的辩论：</b>今年早些时候，我在佛罗里达州的近 1000 人面前就政治和文化中的反犹太主义问题与保守派评论员本·夏皮罗 (Ben Shapiro)<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gh6CYPboQjg">进行了辩论</a>。我们解决了从 Ye 到 Joe Rogan 的所有问题，并且几乎创造了每分钟说出最多单词的世界纪录。 （我成为一名记者的原因之一是人们可以按照自己的速度阅读我的内容，而这在现场听我讲话时是不可能的。）<br><br><b>我回到一首诗或诗行：</b> “把你的面包撒在水面上，因为多日之后，你就会找到它”（传道书 11:1）。有时，写看似无情的社会力量和不公正现象可能会让人感到徒劳。但我发现你永远不知道你的话语会在哪里被听到，以及它们最终会产生什么影响。<br><br><strong>未来一周</strong><br><br><li>安·帕切特 (Ann Patchett) 的新小说《汤姆·莱克》( <a href="https://tertulia.com/book/tom-lake-ann-patchett/9780063327528?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Tom Lake</i></a> ) 探讨了父母在孩子出生前的浪漫史（周二发售）。</li><li>斯特林·哈乔 (Sterlin Harjo) 和塔伊卡·维迪蒂 (Taika Waititi) 创作的喜剧系列<a href="https://www.fxnetworks.com/shows/reservation-dogs"><i>《保留地狗》</i></a>第三季也是最后一季将于周三首播（在 Hulu 上播出）。</li><li>由成龙和塞斯·罗根配音的<a href="https://www.teenagemutantninjaturtlesmovie.com/?gclid=CjwKCAjwzo2mBhAUEiwAf7wjkq5qsml1R5NNWLU67VThcivgiM04HN5SbJI3XqiO_gJTBrbqlNhRyRoCJ0MQAvD_BwE"><i>《忍者神龟：突变混乱》</i></a> （周三上映）<i> </i></li><strong>散文</strong><br><br>美国家庭生活不应该如此动荡<br><br><em>艾略特·哈斯佩尔</em><br><br><p>为人父母总是充满不可预测性：凌晨两点醒来，学校打来电话，那些让<i>我胃痛的</i>可怕话语。这种日常差异通常源于生病或受惊的孩子，并且是家庭生活基本动态的一部分。然而，今天的美国父母也面临着日益严重的外部干扰和旨在提供稳定的机构的退化。其结果是，许多家庭经常会因为一些问题而陷入困境，这些问题不仅仅是不方便，但还不是灾难性的。这会滋生父母的压力、不安全感和疲惫。简而言之，美国人已经进入了一个颤抖的时代。</p><p>过去半个世纪以来，这个国家一直在走这条道路。从 20 世纪 70 年代开始，一系列经济和社会政策决策导致了政治学家雅各布·哈克 (Jacob Hacker) 所说的从政府和企业到家庭的<a href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-great-risk-shift-the-new-economic-insecurity-and-the-decline-of-the-american-dream-jacob-s-hacker/9780190844141?affiliate_id=atl-347">“巨大风险转移”</a> 。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/parenting-challenges-american-families-child-care/674839/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><strong>更多文化内容</strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-richard-rhodes-interview/674828/">奥本海默专家观察<i>奥本海默</i>。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/">格蕾塔·葛韦格在《芭比乐园》中的课程</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/new-york-picking-up-dog-poop/674825/">什么样的恶棍不清理他们的狗？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/lifelong-learning-new-skill-book-recommendations/674807/">终身学习者的七本书</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/the-jewish-catalog-50th-anniversary/674846/">当犹太教走向点菜时</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbenheimer-movie-theaters-hollywood-strikes/674822/">好莱坞的<i>巴本海默</i>失手</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/evolution-liars-of-nature-lixing-sun-review/674808/">大自然会说谎吗？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/a-poem-by-janelle-tan-claude-glass-as-night-song/674800/">诗：《克劳德·格拉斯作为夜歌》</a></li><strong>赶上<em>大西洋</em></strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/chronic-fatigue-long-covid-symptoms/674834/">疲劳会击垮一个人。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2023/07/are-you-plagued-by-the-feeling-that-everyone-used-to-be-nicer/674838/">你是否因为每个人都曾经变得更好的感觉而困扰？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-defies-voting-rights-act-supreme-court/674850/">阿拉巴马州在投票权问题上藐视最高法院。</a></li><strong>相片集</strong><br><br>澳大利亚女足世界杯、巴黎 Lollapalooza 艺术节的表演，以及编辑精选的本周<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-of-the-week-feathered-gorilla-breaching-whale-alphorn-festival/674853/">最佳照片</a>中的更多内容<br><br><i data-stringify-type="italic">Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">探索我们所有的时事通讯。</a></em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/babylon-5-serialized-tv-show-recommendations/674861/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/babylon-5-serialized-tv-show-recommendations/674861/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Weird, Fragmented World of Social Media After Twitter]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>埃隆·马斯克摧毁的公共论坛永远不会被取代——没关系。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/hQLqXeptJBp-yYoePJjV8bbbp_k=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/after_twitter/original.jpg" alt="一只蓝色的鸟在飞离巢穴时掉落羽毛" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">你在蓝天吗</span>？老实说：可能不是。 Twitter 的克隆版仍处于测试阶段，并且其邀请码一直是出了名的吝啬。它的规模较小，这意味着每次新用户涌入时，现有用户群都会感到恐慌，算法策划的“发现”选项卡中充满了令人难以置信的过度抱怨。最近一篇引起广泛讨论的帖子感叹，“蓝天长者”——在这里我应该指出，这是一项在二月份才推出移动版本的服务——因为所有的攻击而遭受着降级的体验。这句话已经成为一个即时模因。<br><br>关于 Bluesky，您只需要了解两件事。首先，它的用户正试图让<em>“skeeting”</em>一词成为现实，尽管它是比 Mastodon 的<em>“tooting”</em>更糟糕的<em>推文</em>替代方案。第二是它始终处于高度情绪化状态。现在，滚动 Twitter 的“为你”选项卡就像在装满业余种族科学家和罗马雕像化身的碗里捞苹果，哀叹我们不再建造大教堂，而 Bluesky 的类似内容则讨论了向网站开发者发送死亡威胁是否合理。如果他们确实值得的话，这是可以接受的。<br><br>据我所知，Bluesky 正在吸走 Twitter 上情绪最失调的用户和最忠实的垃圾发布者。我不敢在那里发帖——根据追踪服务，我的账户曾一度是该应用程序上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://wolfgang.raios.xyz/top_blocked">被封锁最多的</a>账户——但很高兴看到一个小而紧密、政治上独特的社区已经形成，尽管围绕着包括仇恨在内的共同利益我。虽然 Bluesky 的规模只是大型社交网络的一小部分，但它似乎已经达到了维持自身所需的临界质量，这表明埃隆·马斯克在 Twitter 上的行为已经无可挽回地破坏了该服务。无论从字面上还是隐喻上来说，我们现在都生活在后推特时代。马斯克重塑品牌后， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/"><em>X</em></a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/">标志着很多人不再愿意去的地方</a>。<br><br>直到最近，我还怀疑即使是像马斯克这样草率、反复无常的老板也能打垮 Twitter。留在那里的自恋者和瘾君子会让藤壶相形见绌。该网站一直比 Facebook 小得多，它之所以重要只是因为政客、记者和目前被认为是公共知识分子的人都在使用它。无论您阅读<em>《</em><em>纽约时报》</em>还是观看福克斯新闻，您都会遇到源自 Twitter 的内容。当推特将唐纳德·特朗普踢出局时，这严重削弱了他破坏新闻议程的能力，因为记者根本不准备加入这位前总统本人控制的右翼平台“真相社会”。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/05/social-media-democracy-trust-babel/629369/">摘自2022年5月号：为什么过去10年美国人的生活特别愚蠢</a><br><br>不过现在，我可以看到后 Twitter 世界的第一缕曙光。怪人、早期采用者、垃圾海报、毛茸茸的人和责骂者正在尝试 Bluesky，在那里他们可以抱怨“Elmo”和他负责“鸟类网站”的任期。真正的年轻人都在使用 TikTok。真正的婴儿潮一代从未在 Twitter 上出现过，但仍然很高兴<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/10/facebook-midlife-crisis-boomerbook/620307/">在 Facebook 上发布</a>有关 UFO 和 Bunco 之夜的内容。一些心怀不满的推特用户尝试了 Post 和 Mastodon，但第一个是墓地，第二个是非技术用户的障碍训练场。普通人和品牌转向 Instagram 的新 Threads 应用程序，然后许多普通人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://uk.pcmag.com/social-media/147939/yikes-threads-user-traffic-falls-74-from-initial-high">立即离开</a>，因为 Threads 太无聊了，没有足够的怪人、毛茸茸的人或责骂来添加调味品。 （企业可能喜欢将广告放在无可争议的励志内容旁边，但累积的效果是让 Threads 就像观看完全由电视广告组成的电视频道一样。） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i9rVcCR5IQE">Grindfluencers</a> - 听 15 分钟<em>《魔鬼经济学</em>》和<em>《艺术》</em>摘要的人<em>of War——</em>一直在 LinkedIn 上最开心，发布他们的播客内容并祝贺你的“工作周年纪念日”，这不是也永远不会是真实的事情。 Instagram 上仍然充满了感到#blessed 的性感人士，并热衷于穿着比基尼在无边泳池边摆​​姿势来展示这种谦逊。 （如果这些海报上有一个性感的妹妹，她也可以穿比基尼，然后他们就可以观察到#familyiseverything。） Twitter 现在是那些知道<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://unherd.com/thepost/did-the-desantis-campaign-know-it-was-using-a-nazi-symbol/">Sonnenrad</a>是什么并且相信它已经成为人们的首选社交网络。受到不公正的诽谤。<br><br>有些人会在考虑了上述所有选项后，最终决定接触草地。<br><br>社交媒体早期<span class="smallcaps">的许多争议都</span>源于这样的假设：用户在跨平台上拥有单一、一致的身份。研究人员达纳·博伊德和爱丽丝·马威克将由此产生的不和谐<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/31/web-concepts-need-understand-2015-guide-netiquette">描述</a>为“语境崩溃”：用户在 Twitter 或 Facebook 上潜在的无限受众面前，像在私人房间里一样随意发言，招致批评。很多时候，两个亲密朋友之间本可以致命的笑话在<em>BuzzFeed</em>列表文章或电视新闻 chyron 中却遭到更广泛的反对。现在我们已经更擅长在不同的空间将自己分类为不同的模式，以至于我看到人们感叹他们在 Instagram 上知道自己是谁，在 Twitter 上知道自己是谁，<em>但我不知道自己是谁在线程上</em>。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/">Yair Rosenberg：如何挽救社交媒体</a><br><br>考虑到这一趋势，令人惊讶的不是 Twitter 现在已经分裂，而是它持续了这么久。多年来，这里一直是角斗士和狮子自愿加入的竞技场。 Twitter 允许对库进行恶意攻击，也允许库针对规模稍小的库发起取消活动。<br><br>那健康吗？很长一段时间，我都担心 Upworthy 联合创始人 Eli Pariser 所说的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ted.com/talks/eli_pariser_beware_online_filter_bubbles?language=en">过滤气泡</a>”的扩散，他将其定义为“你生活在网上的个人的、独特的信息宇宙”。我想，也许两极分化是由于我们被囚禁在回音室中而导致的，而我们正在屈服于多元化的无知——缺乏对多数观点的认识。现在我想知道过去十年的社交媒体是否让我们在另一个方向上走得太远，花太多时间与与我们不同的人在一起，以夸大我们差异的方式聚集在一起。<br><br> 2018 年，理性主义博主斯科特·亚历山大 (Scott Alexander) 发表了一篇名为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slatestarcodex.com/2018/10/30/sort-by-controversial/">按争议排序</a>”的短篇小说。其中，一名科技初创公司的员工发明了一个程序，可以输出“剪刀声明”——立即将群体分成两半的断言。世界避免陷入无休无止的低级战争，只是因为她不小心创造了一份剪刀声明，在公司工作完成之前将公司撕裂。这个故事抓住了社交媒体作为对阳光下每个主题进行滚动公投的感觉。您是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/columnist/2023/05/26/can-i-recline-my-seat-on-a-plane/70253628007/">飞机座椅</a>躺椅吗？如果来访的孩子在您家呆到很晚，您必须为他们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2022/06/04/1103075936/-swedengate-alleges-the-swedes-dont-feed-other-peoples-children-on-playdates">提供</a>晚餐吗？ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.buzzfeed.com/catesish/help-am-i-going-insane-its-definitely-blue">这件衣服</a>是蓝色的还是白色的？在政治辩论中，这意味着被迫灌输政治对手最令人头疼的痴迷。以 Twitter 账户 Libs of TikTok 为例，该账户的存在纯粹是为了从一个社交网络收集超前卫的观点，并将其提供给另一个社交网络作为愤怒的诱饵。它的流行让我认为过滤气泡，至少以温和的形式，可能不是一个坏主意。<br><br>为了蓬勃发展，社区需要界限和规范，甚至，上帝保佑我们，长辈。这就是为什么我喜欢把鼻子伸进 Bluesky 并时常深吸一口气。对于那些对动漫生殖器和有关米奇·麦康奈尔的残酷笑话都感兴趣的人们来说，这是一个有围墙的花园。他们在那里很开心。你可能不会。没关系。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-alternatives-bluesky-mastodon-threads/674859/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-alternatives-bluesky-mastodon-threads/674859/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[One More COVID Summer?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>年中浪潮可能正在连续第四年酝酿。会一直这样吗？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/ho_TtxSm1W41SD_VW5hNZB-_8Eo=/1x0:965x542/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/SummerCovid2/original.gif" alt="冠状病毒粒子的动画，太阳和云在其内部移动" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>保罗·斯佩拉/大西洋月刊；资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>自疫情爆发初期以来，流行病学家就一直在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/11/covid-seasonal-winter/620766/">等待</a>冠状病毒最终摆脱泛季节狂潮。不会再有像 2020 年第一波袭击美国那样的春季浪潮，也不会再有像当年掀起热疫苗夏季浪潮的年中浪潮。最终，或者说希望落空了，SARS-CoV-2将遵循许多其他呼吸道病原体所遵循的相同日历，至少在全球温带地区：一个严酷的冬季高峰，然后是一个休假的夏季。<br><br>但疫情爆发已经三年半了，冠状病毒仍然顽固地拒绝让最温暖的月份休息一下。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://yourlocalepidemiologist.substack.com/p/covid-19-catch-up-quick">一些</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://caitlinrivers.substack.com/p/this-week-in-outbreaks-july-28-edition">公共卫生专家</a>现在担心，在经历了一段相对平静的时期后，该病毒正在掀起另一波夏季浪潮。在美国南部和东北部，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://biobot.io/data/">废水</a>中冠状病毒的浓度几周来一直在缓慢上升，中西部和西部地区也紧随其后；检测阳性率、急诊室诊断出的 COVID-19 以及<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#maps_new-admissions-rate-county">住院人数</a>也在上升。绝对数字仍然很小，而且可能会保持这种状态。但约翰霍普金斯大学的流行病学家凯特琳·里弗斯表示，这些都是年中浪潮正在酝酿的明显早期迹象，这将使今年夏天连续第四个夏天出现明显的冠状病毒爆发。<br><br>然而，即使疫情已经蔓延到如此程度，仍然没有人能确定夏季浪潮是否是新冠病毒的永久常态，或者该病毒是否表现出可预测的季节性模式。没有任何自然法则规定冬天一定会出现呼吸道疾病，或者夏天则不会。 “我们只是不太了解是什么驱动了呼吸道感染的周期性模式，”东北大学传染病建模师萨姆·斯卡皮诺（Sam Scarpino）说。这意味着今年任何时候这种病毒都无法保证让我们有任何懈怠。<br><br>许多病原体<em>会</em>随着季节的变化而盛衰，这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.plos.org/plospathogens/article?id=10.1371/journal.ppat.1007327">无可争议的</a>。在世界温带地区，空气中的虫子在冬天会大量繁殖，但在炎热的天气里就会被抑制。与此同时，脊髓灰质炎和其他粪便传播的病原体以及淋病和其他一些性传播感染通常在夏季上升。但注意到这些趋势是一回事，另一回事是另一回事。真正理解触发因素是另一回事。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/11/covid-seasonal-winter/620766/">阅读：新冠病毒现在看起来确实是季节性的</a><br><br>有些疾病更容易解释：在赤道附近，寨卡病毒和基孔肯雅热等<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5963813/">蚊媒疾病</a>的浪潮往往与携带它们的昆虫依赖天气的生命周期有关；在世界温带地区，莱姆病的发病率与夏季蜱虫的活动有关。流感也有相当有力的数据支持其对冬季的偏好。这种病毒包裹在一层称为包膜的脆弱脂肪层中，通过湿滴在空气中传播。在凉爽干燥的条件下传播得最好，这种条件可能有助于保持传染性颗粒的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/mbio.03452-22">完整性</a>并在空中飞沫。<br><br>冠状病毒与流感有足够的相似之处，大多数专家预计它也会在冬季继续传播。这两种病毒都存在于敏感的皮肤中。两者都喜欢通过气溶胶移动。两者都是相对较快的进化者，往往不会产生持久的抗感染免疫力，而这些因素有利于以相当稳定的速度重复攻击人群。出于这些原因，埃默里大学病毒学家 Anice Lowen 预计 SARS-CoV-2 将继续表现出“世界温带地区明显的冬季季节性”。冬季也是我们的身体<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev-virology-012420-022445">更容易受到</a>呼吸道细菌感染的时期：寒冷、干燥的空气会干扰将微生物从鼻子和喉咙中排出的粘液的运动；干旱还会使这些通道内的细胞枯萎和死亡。由于维生素 D 供应不足，某些免疫防御系统可能会变得有些困倦。<br><br>这些都不能阻止 SARS-CoV-2 在炎热的天气中传播，即使专家们不确定该病毒为何如此容易引发夏季浪潮。许多其他微生物也可以控制它：肠道病毒、脊髓灰质炎等等。即使是鼻病毒和腺病毒这两种最常见的感冒原因，也往往会全年传播，有时会在一年中最热的月份中肆虐。 （许多科学家推测这与这些病毒相对坚固的外层有关，但原因无疑比这更复杂。）对新冠病毒夏季浪潮的一个经常吹捧的解释是，该国某些地区的人们躲在室内，以避暑。战胜炎热。但洛文告诉我，这个论点本身“是站不住脚的”。在工业化国家，人们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cpsc.gov/safety-education/safety-guides/home/indoor-air-pollution-introduction-health-professionals">90% 以上的时间都在室内度过</a>。<br><br>也就是说，许多小的影响的积累可以共同创造一个季节性的临界点。夏季<em>是</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://aytm.com/post/vacations-survey">特别受欢迎的旅行季节</a>，经常参加大型聚会。里弗斯说，距离冬季还有好几个月，感染和疫苗接种也很多，每年的这个时候，人群免疫力也可能处于相对较低的水平。此外，尽管 SARS-CoV-2 与流感有很多相似之处，但它本身就是一种野兽：迄今为止，它对人类的影响更长期、更<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2022/12/covid-common-cold-status-differentiation/672472/">严重</a>，并且以更快的速度产生席卷人群的变种。这些动态都会影响波浪何时出现。<br><br>尽管某些身体防御能力确实会在寒冷中下降，但数据并不支持夏季免疫力单方面更强的观点。纽约“我们行动环境正义”组织的环境健康主任米凯拉·马丁内斯告诉我，情况远比这复杂。多年来，她和其他研究人员一直在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8987173/">收集</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33817568/">证据</a>，表明我们的身体具有明显的季节性免疫特征——一些防御分子在夏季出现峰值，而另一些则在冬季出现峰值。这些转变的后果尚不明显。但其中一些可以帮助解释冠状病毒何时传播。同样的道理，冬季也不是疾病肆虐的时期。瑞典卡罗林斯卡研究所的免疫学家 Xaquin Castro Dopico 发现，北半球的免疫系统<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25965853/">在冬天可能更容易发炎——</a>是的，这可能会使某些疾病发作更加严重，但也可以改善<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19889749/">反应</a>对于某些疫苗接种。<br><br>所有这些解释都可能适用于新冠病毒夏季的波动——或者也许没有一个适用。 “每个人都希望得到一个非常简单的季节性答案，”马丁内斯告诉我。但这种情况可能根本不存在。马丁内斯告诉我，即使是小儿麻痹症这种在美国被消灭之前的严重<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4474890/">夏季</a>疾病，其季节性的原因几十年来也一直是“一个悬而未决的问题”。<br><br>里弗斯希望，冠状病毒的永久模式可能已经开始显现：冬季的鼎盛时期，以及夏季可能出现的较小的驼峰。 “我们已经进入第四年了，我们年复一年地看到同样的事情，”她告诉我。但一些专家担心，讨论 COVID-19 季节性还为时过早。 SARS-CoV-2 对人类来说仍然很新鲜，其模式<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/03/kids-babies-getting-covid-exposure-vaccines/673368/">可能与最终形式相去甚远</a>。在极端情况下，研究人员在大流行最初几年观察到的模式可能根本无法预示未来，因为它们概括了如此多的变化：最初缺乏免疫力和快速获得免疫力、病毒的进化、病毒的潮起潮落。面具，等等。耶鲁大学传染病建模师布兰登·奥格布努 (Brandon Ogbunu) 表示，在这种相互抵消的影响中，“你会得到一些违反直觉的动态”，而这种动态不一定会持续很长时间。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/03/kids-babies-getting-covid-exposure-vaccines/673368/">阅读：新冠疫情的下一阶段现已开始</a><br><br><br>由于现在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.healthdata.org/sites/default/files/files/1_briefing_Global_6.pdf">世界上很多地方都</a>受到感染、接种疫苗或两者兼而有之，而且新冠疫情缓解措施几乎完全消失，全球局势现在的变化不再那么大。病毒本身虽然仍然明显以惊人的速度发生变化，但在一年半多的时间里还没有实现 Omicron 级别的进化跳跃。但目前还没有人能够保证其可预测性。疫苗接种的节奏尚未确定；东北大学的斯卡皮诺也不准备否认病毒进化意外的想法。也许夏季浪潮的发生就表明 SARS-CoV-2 仍将是四季皆宜的微生物。或者它们可能是这场大流行病的死亡之声的一部分——系统中尚未平静下来的噪音。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/summer-covid-wave-2023/674863/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/summer-covid-wave-2023/674863/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Misunderstood Reason Millions of Americans Stopped Going to Church]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>驱赶人们出走的决定性问题是……21世纪美国人的生活是如何运作的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/SNLWHQRKMYXKJeLjdVhRTWLZR4Q=/0x312:3000x2000/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_455600083/original.jpg" alt="长椅上放着一本圣经。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>斯宾塞普拉特/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>在内布拉斯加州林肯市的童年教堂里，几乎所有和我一起长大的人都不再是基督徒了。这并不罕见。过去 25 年里，四千万美国人不再去教堂。这大约占总人口的 12%，这是美国历史上教堂出席率最大的集中变化。作为一名基督徒，我敏锐地感受到这种转变。我和我的妻子想知道那些帮助我们维护自己信仰的机构和社区是否仍然会为我们的四个孩子而存在，更不用说有一天我们可能会有孙子孙女。<br><br>这一变化对整个美国来说也是个坏消息：参与宗教团体通常与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2016/10/28/religion-church-attendance-mortality-column/92676964/">更好的健康状况、更长的寿命</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.philanthropyroundtable.org/magazine/less-god-less-giving/">更高的经济慷慨度</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thepublicdiscourse.com/2018/03/20935/">更稳定的家庭</a>相关——所有这些对于一个孤独率上升的国家来说是迫切需要的、精神疾病、酒精和药物依赖。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/christianity-secularization-america-renewal-modernity/672948/">蒂莫西·凯勒：美国基督教即将复兴</a><br><br>奥兰多福音派教会的牧师吉姆·戴维斯 (Jim Davis) 和福音联盟 (Gospel Coalition) 作家迈克尔·格雷厄姆 (Michael Graham) 撰写的一本新书借鉴了政治学家瑞安·伯吉 (Ryan Burge) 和保罗·朱佩 (Paul Djupe) 对 7,000 多名美国人进行的调查，试图解释为什么人们离开教堂——用书中的行话来说是“去教堂”——以及可以采取什么措施让一些人回来。这本书提出了一个有趣的可能性：如果问题不是教会对成员的要求太多，而是他们要求的不够呢？<br><br><i>大洗礼</i>发现，教会中的宗教滥用和更普遍的道德腐败已经驱赶了人们。当然，这是对许多领袖失败的控诉，他们没有解决教会中的虐待问题。但戴维斯和格雷厄姆还发现，离开教会的人中有很大一部分是出于更平庸的原因而这样做的。这本书指出，驱逐大多数离开者的决定性问题是……21世纪美国人的生活是如何运作的。当代美国根本就不是为了促进相互、关怀或共同生活而设立的。相反，它旨在最大限度地提高职业和财务成功所定义的个人成就。这样的制度给各种形式的社区留下了宝贵的时间和精力，而这些社区对一个人自己的职业生活没有贡献，或者随着年龄的增长，对自己孩子的职业前景没有贡献。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/02/religion-workism-making-americans-miserable/583441/">工作主义</a>在美国占主导地位，正因为如此， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hhs.gov/about/news/2023/05/03/new-surgeon-general-advisory-raises-alarm-about-devastating-impact-epidemic-loneliness-isolation-united-states.html">美国的社区</a>，包括宗教社区，是一个无法相加的数学问题。<br><br>许多在教会环境中遭受虐待的受害者都可以体会到他们失去信仰能力的时刻，他们几乎感觉自己的信仰正在流失。不过，这本书表明，对于大多数曾经是教会成员但后来离开的美国人来说，离开的过程是渐进的，在许多情况下，他们甚至没有意识到这已经发生了。这不像是从悬崖上跳下来，而更像是开车冲下斜坡，最终意识到你再也看不到你出发的地方了。<br><br>考虑一下格雷厄姆和戴维斯在书中用来描述典型福音派教会成员的复合人物之一：一位在郊区大型教堂长大的 30 多岁女性，在大学期间大力投入校园事工，毕业后搬到了找到了一份全职工作，并开始参加当地教堂的一个年轻人团体。在她 20 多岁的时候，她遇到了一个不太热衷于宗教的男人，他们结婚了，在婚姻早期的某个时刻，在他们的第一个或第二个孩子出生后，他们不再去教堂。也许宝宝睡得不好，当周日早上到来时，呆在家里并在宝宝（最终）入睡时抓住任何可以睡觉的时间会更容易。<br><br>在其他情况下，一个人可能正进入职业生涯中期，从事一项需要每周工作 60 或 70 小时的高压力工作。再加上 15 个小时的通勤时间，突然之间，他们一周的清醒时间已经占到了三分之二。因此，当朋友邀请他们参加周日早上的早午餐时，他们可能想去教堂，但他们也想见那个朋友，因为他们已经好几个月没见到他们了。朋友赢了。<br><br>无论哪种情况几周后，周日去教堂的想法都会带来一定的精神负担——你可能<i>想去</i>，但你也害怕不可避免的关于你去过哪里的问题。当你在脑海中排练对话时，“我没去教堂去和朋友一起吃早午餐”或“我太累了，不能来”听起来不像是令人信服的借口。很快，听起来参加比逃课更难，即使你的某些部分仍然想参加。对许多人来说，潜在的挑战是他们的生活就像一根即将断裂的橡皮筋一样被拉伸，而去教堂最终感觉就像是清单上已经太长的一项。<br><br>在这样的背景下，教会可以做什么？理论上，基督教会可以成为这一切的解药。在我们这个时代，还有什么比一个以真诚的爱为标志的社区更需要的呢？根据每个人的能力和需要分享他们所拥有的东西，定期一起吃饭，慷慨地为邻居服务，并过着安静的美德和祈祷的生活？一个健康的教会可以成为严峻的美国经济中的安全网，在需要时向其成员提供物质援助：婴儿出生后的膳食，裁员后的租金。也许更重要的是，它提醒人们，他们的身份不在于他们的工作或他们赚了多少钱；而在于他们的身份。他们是上帝的孩子，受到爱护和保护，具有无限的价值。<br><br>但一个充满活力、赋予生命的教会需要其成员更多而不是更少的时间和精力。它要求人们将彼此置于事业之上，将祈祷和阅读经文置于成就之上。在一个非教会化的时代，这似乎是一个艰难的推销。如果人们已经离开——特别是如果他们离开是因为他们感到太忙、精疲力尽而无法定期去教堂——为什么他们想成为一个对他们要求如此之高的教会的一员呢？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/01/us-religious-affiliation-rates-declining/672729/">阅读：美国宗教尚未消亡</a><br><br>虽然可以理解，但这并不是一个正确的问题。我们面前的问题并不是我们有一个健康、可持续发展的社会，却没有教会的空间。问题在于，许多美国人所采用的生活方式让我们感到孤独、焦虑，并且不确定如何与其他人一起生活。<br><br>美国教会的悲剧在于，他们如此陷入同一个世界，以至于我们现在发现他们无法为这些受苦的人们提供任何在其他地方更容易找到的东西。美国教会常常满足于充当一种模糊的精神非政府组织，一个由独立的个人组成的组织，他们聚集在一起进行宗教服务，以激励他们，提供实际的生活建议，或提供积极的情感体验。很多时候，并不是一个社区能够通过其传教和生活来见证另一种生活方式。<br><br>神学家斯坦利·豪尔（Stanley Hauer） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.christiancentury.org/article/interview/dangers-providing-pastoral-care">很好地抓住了这个问题</a>，他说：“教牧关怀已经变得痴迷于发达工业社会中人们的个人创伤，他们发现自己的生活缺乏意义。”困难在于，我们当前的秩序所造成的许多伤口和疼痛并不是可以控制或消除的。只有通过改变一个人的生活，成为一个属于完全不同类型的社区的完全不同类型的人，才能解决这些问题。<br><br>去年秋天，我在纽约待了几天，期间参观了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bruderhof.com/">一群和平主义基督徒</a>拥有的房屋，他们靠共同的钱包生活——这意味着成员们没有私人财产，而是分享他们的财产和金钱。他们简单的生活和共同的财务使他们的日程安排更加灵活，从而形成了更紧密的直接社区和对邻居更大的慷慨，以及更丰富的祈祷生活和个人对上帝的奉献，所有这些都得到了对教会的坚定承诺的支持。<br><br>诚然，这是一个极端的例子。但这个社区的蓬勃发展并不是因为它找到了减少对其成员提出的要求的方法，而是因为它找到了一种增加成员相互提供的东西的方法。他们的生活方式使他们摆脱了工作主义的束缚。在这个社区中，评判工作的标准不是它所产生的金钱，而是它所服务的人。在相信 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mereorthodoxy.com/dignity-beyond-accomplishment">尊严建立在成就之上的</a>工人主义文化中，简单地收回这种另一种形式的尊严就变成了一种激进的行为。<br><br>在福音书中，耶稣告诉他的第一批门徒抛弃他们旧的生活方式，甚至放弃他们所在的犁或渔网，如果有必要，甚至留下他们的父母。一个对彼此至少没有这么多期望的教会并不是耶稣所说的真正的教会。如果格雷厄姆和戴维斯是对的，那么它也很可能无法在我们今天面临的挑战中幸存下来。<br><br>大规模的去教会可能是教会新时刻的开始，这个时刻不再那么渴望受人尊敬和成功，也不再那么关注个人与美国价值观和假设的一致。我们可以见证美国传统成功衡量标准之外的另一种生活方式。教会可以塑造更好、更真实的社区，让饥饿者得到食物，弱者得到提升，骄傲者被贬低。这些团体可能没有许多美国教会近年来经常追求的金钱、成功和影响力。但如果这些社区看起来不太像那些教堂，它们也可能看起来更像耶稣期望他的追随者创建的那种社区。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/christian-church-communitiy-participation-drop/674843/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/christian-church-communitiy-participation-drop/674843/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Studios Are Risking Everything]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>长期罢工可能会导致电影院停业。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/QPwGjAj5qgmmN-Hh5jMJnG-Ca40=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/studios_strike/original.jpg" alt="空荡荡的电影院和空白屏幕的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>千年图片/图库库存</figcaption></figure>停工首先是为了钱，同时发生的美国演员工会和美国作家工会的罢工也不例外。演员和编剧想要更多，也希望限制人工智能的使用。制片厂表示，考虑到他们在建立流媒体服务时产生的巨额费用，他们分发的内容几乎没有演员和编剧想要的那么多。他们发现自己陷入了僵局，将行业最重要的资产之一：电影院置于危险之中，从而有可能进一步减少总收益。<br><br>好莱坞有这样的历史：首先将不断变化的消费者习惯视为对影院收入的威胁，然后将其视为追求赚取更大利润的工具。电影公司起初对是否将电影授权给电视网络犹豫不决，然后意识到小屏幕是一个尚未开发的市场。好莱坞与 VHS 进行了殊死搏斗——担心非法盗版和客户合法录制电影制片厂授权给电视和有线电视网络的电影——直到它意识到家庭录像租赁和销售是一座金矿。 VHS 的继任者 DVD <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/08/the-death-of-the-dvd-why-sales-dropped-more-than-86percent-in-13-years.html">的年销售额在 2005 年达到顶峰，达到 163 亿美元</a>，几乎<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.boxofficemojo.com/year/?ref_=bo_nb_yld_secondarytab">是国内票房的两倍</a>，之后因流媒体而出现下滑。在某些方面，院线几乎成了家庭录像带销售的亏本产品。<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gF6K2IxC9O8">正如马特·达蒙（Matt Damon）所说</a>，家庭录像带的销售实际上帮助支撑了“我喜欢的电影类型”（成人电影）的整个市场。<br><br>流媒体的诞生——特别是 Netflix 在线组件的兴起——恰逢 DVD 销量的下降，这为 Netflix 的老板们创造了机会。 “一旦它为观众提供了在客厅沙发上在线观看电影和电视节目的新方式……订阅量猛增了 63%，”Dade Hayes 和 Dawn Chmielewski 在他们的书<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/binge-times-inside-hollywood-s-furious-billion-dollar-battle-to-take-down-netflix-dade-hayes/9780062980007?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《Binge Times: Inside Hollywood&#39;s Furious Billion-Dollar》</em></a>中写道。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/binge-times-inside-hollywood-s-furious-billion-dollar-battle-to-take-down-netflix-dade-hayes/9780062980007?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>打倒 Netflix 之战</em></a><em>。</em> “新兴的流媒体服务的发展是以好莱坞为代价的。 [首席执行官里德]黑斯廷斯和公司巧妙地利用了工作室的薪酬结构，当高管实现财务目标时，他们会支付丰厚的奖金。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/writers-strike-hollywood-wga-union-streaming-platforms/674056/">加文·穆勒：好莱坞的卢德分子</a><br><br>其先发优势、从目光短浅的好莱坞高管手中收购的庞大电影库，以及<em>《纸牌屋</em>》、 <em>《女子监狱</em>》和<em>《怪奇物语》</em>等热门原创剧集，帮助 Netflix 成为一家<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.yahoo.com/now/netflix-full-2022-earnings-eps-121625446.html">去年在全球创造收入超过 310 亿美元的</a>公司。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.yahoo.com/now/netflix-full-2022-earnings-eps-121625446.html">今年</a>，大约是 2019 年（新冠疫情爆发前的最后<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2020/film/box-office/box-office-us-misses-record-disney-dominates-1203453752/">一年）全球所有电影制片厂票房总和的四分之三</a>。这就是该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX">市值</a>达到 1900 亿美元左右的原因。<br><br>电影公司和他们的企业霸主看着 Netflix 的股价和收入，想知道为什么他们也不能印钞票。这就是为什么在大流行开始之前，工作室都在计划自己转向流媒体。疫情爆发后，他们先跳了起来，但很快就发现自己被淹死了。<br><br>正如马修·鲍尔（Matthew Ball）在他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thestreamingbook.com/">对迄今为止的流媒体战争的权威看法</a>中指出的那样，电影公司向流媒体的转型充满了忧虑，结果也好坏参半。以 NBCUniversal 的竞争者 Peacock 为例，该公司暂时有望实现订阅人数和收入双丰收，但仍在大量流失现金。 “康卡斯特最初表示，从 2020 年到 2024 年，Peacock 单年亏损不会超过 $1B，累积亏损将达到 $2B 峰值，并在 2024 年实现盈亏平衡。然而，Peacock 在 2020 年亏损了 $663MM，$1.7B鲍尔<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thestreamingbook.com/chapters/three-years-into-hollywoods-five-year-plan">写道</a>：“2021 年将损失 2.5 亿美元，2022 年将损失 2.5 亿美元。目前累计损失超过 5 亿美元。”除了有关 Netflix 的新闻外，有关流媒体服务的大多数正面头条<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/05/disney-plus-loses-subscribers-streaming-quarter-bob-iger-1235362109/">都可以归结为</a>“好吧，他们本季度的损失比分析师预期的要少一些”。<br><br>对于大多数这些公司来说，问题不在于收入，而在于收入。这是支出。直到最近，人们花在电视节目和电影上的钱比以往任何时候都多。正如美国电影协会在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.motionpictures.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/MPA-2021-THEME-Report-FINAL.pdf">其 2021 年娱乐业状况报告</a>中指出的那样，2021 年通过流媒体、有线和广播制作了 1,826 部原创剧集。从 2019 年到 2021 年，通过流媒体频道发布的电视节目数量大约增加了一倍。<br><br>制片厂看到这一点后表示：“更多的编剧和演员正在获得更多的工作。你还想从我们这里得到什么？”正如编剧扎克·斯坦茨 (Zack Stentz) 在<em>《纽约时报》</em>上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/30/opinion/hollywood-writers-guild-strike.html">指出的</a>那样，“在流媒体驱动的繁荣时期”报告收入的 WGA 会员数量“从 4,500 人猛增至 6,000 多人”。 WGA 报告称，2022 年收取的费用比以往任何时候都多，匿名流媒体内部人士 Entertainment Strategy Guy 表示，这意味着 WGA 编剧的总薪酬<em>可能</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://entertainmentstrategyguy.com/2023/07/20/exclusive-wga-screenwriter-earnings-likely-broke-records-in-2022/">比以往任何时候都多</a>。这就是为什么迪士尼首席执行​​官鲍勃·艾格（Bob Iger） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/bob-iger-writers-actors-strike-disney-ceo-1235669169/">在电视上轻松自在地表示</a>编剧和演员不切实际，认为“他们正在加剧这个行业已经面临的一系列挑战，坦率地说，这是非常具有破坏性的” ”。<br><br>随着电影公司开始将电影从上映日程上取消，这种混乱即将来临。由赞达亚领衔的米高梅新类型“网球三人组电影”影片《<em>挑战者</em>》 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/film/global/challengers-zendaya-skips-venice-film-festival-sag-aftra-strike-1235672841/">原定在今年的威尼斯电影节上开幕</a>；时间被推迟到 2024 年，希望这位演员届时能够走上红地毯。探照灯影业 (Searchlight Pictures) 将于 9 月至 12 月<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/searchlights-poor-things-emma-stone-september-december-1235447551/">推出</a>欧格斯·兰斯莫斯 (Yorgos Lanthimos) 的新片《可怜的事物》( <em>Poor Things)</em> 。伊森·科恩的<em>《Drive-Away Dolls》</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/dune-part-two-drive-away-dolls-actors-strike-box-office-1235448062/">可能会错过秋季音乐节巡演</a>。 A24 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/a24-problemista-actors-strike-wga-strike-1235444874/">还取消了<em>Problemista 的</em>8 月发布日期</a>。华纳兄弟<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2023/07/dune-part-two-may-be-delayed-thanks-to-hollywoods-strikes#:~:text=Dune%3A%20Part%20Two%2C%20director%20Denis,of%20discussions%20told%20the%20outlet.">可能会</a>取消<em>《沙丘：第二部分》</em>的 11 月上映日期。这将使票房相对贫瘠。<br><br>作为一个在 2020 年一整年都在观看电影制片厂的人，反复将电影推迟三个月（或六、九）个月，希望在大流行消退后上映，我很遗憾地说，这开始让人感觉像新冠疫情重演一样可疑。需要明确的是，只要罢工持续下去，推迟上映日期对于工作室来说是完全合乎逻辑的举动：没有明星就意味着没有促销。但我担心，继之前影院长时间缺席电影之后，影院的电影数量如此之少，可能意味着不再有影院了。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/05/hollywood-writers-strike-wga/673926/">阅读：为什么你应该关注好莱坞作家的罢工</a><br><br>这也许有点夸张，但也只是轻微夸张。在大流行期间停工期间，美国的屏幕数量<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-news/movie-theater-screen-losses-ticket-prices-1235346523/">减少了 5%</a> ；损害没有更严重的唯一原因是 AMC 在 2021 年不太可能成为一只迷因股票，这帮助该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.polygon.com/movies/2021/1/29/22256360/amc-stock-price-reddit-rally-robinhood-debt-conversion">偿还了 6 亿美元的债务</a>。但<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.boxofficemojo.com/year/ytd/">今年迄今为止，</a>票房收入仍比 2019 年低近 20%，比 2018 年低近 25%。观众对与大流行相关的影院关闭相对理解，并已开始回归，但在事情重回正轨时再次让他们放弃看电影的习惯可能会产生可怕的后果。<br><br>这些后果对于该行业的<em>每个人</em>来说都是可怕的。院线上映仍然是任何一部电影货币化的最佳且最一致的个人方式。它们是电影<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thebulwark.com/moving-films-to-vod-cant-make-up-the-revenue-the-traditional-theatrical-model-generates/">收入瀑布</a>的顶端。尽管某些电影（尤其是中低预算影片）从非院线收入中获得的总收入可能高于院线收入，但在完成盈利能力方面，院线发行仍然是最大的难题。即使是家庭发行方面的成功实验<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/07/business/media/universal-premium-video-on-demand.html">，例如环球影业的高级视频点播窗口</a>（制片厂对仍在影院上映的大片收取额外费用），也依赖于影院放映所带来的声望提升。影院上映是顾客愿意花 20 美元租一部电影的原因。<br><br>所有这些都表明，艾格在一个非常狭隘的意义上是正确的：这对娱乐业来说是一个颠覆性的时期，长时间的关闭可能是灾难性的，导致每个人的钱都减少。但这种因新冠疫情而加速的破坏是工作室自己希望复制 Netflix 模式的直接结果，并将院线上映的承重墙视为装饰性的小玩意，很容易拆除，以完成一些花哨的开放式平面图。是华纳兄弟探索频道首席执行官大卫·扎斯拉夫 (David Zaslav) 钟爱的 HGTV 播出的家居装修节目中的首选。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-actor-guild-strike/674848/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-actor-guild-strike/674848/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[America Is Drowning in Packages]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在亚马逊时代，UPS 工人的工作是不可能完成的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/V6dZ4_O0a4054tchlComWJ1bWms=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/ups_final_2/original.jpg" alt="被包裹包围的地球仪" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>当 UPS 送货工人上次罢工是在 1997 年时，他们的工作性质截然不同。亚马逊当时还只是一家在线书店，距首次销售仅两年时间。购买牛仔裤、新家具或其他任何东西，仍然需要大多数人开车前往当地购物中心。当国际卡车司机兄弟会周二宣布它已与 UPS 达成一项临时协议时，该协议将避免罢工并让数十万工会成员保住工作，这些工人在美国人生活中的角色已经发生了根本性的变化。<br><br>新合同还需要得到工会成员的批准，它来得也不算太早。 UPS 处理的货物数量如此之大，据该公司估计，其员工所处理的货物约占该国国内生产总值的 6%，并且该公司运送的包裹占美国所有包裹的近四分之一。互联网零售和满足其需求的送货服务量使美国更加依赖困难的劳动密集型工作，即所谓的最后一英里包裹递送。该国的基础设施和劳动力仍在努力追赶。<br><br>即使在亚马逊时代，现在在美国递送的包裹数量听起来也是完全荒谬的。 2000 年，美国邮政服务公司（美国最大的包裹托运商）递送了 24 亿个包裹。到 2022 年，这一数字已激增至 72 亿。 UPS 现在每年处理 52 亿个国内包裹，而 2000 年处理的包裹数量为 32 亿个，而亚马逊的物流业务<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-to-launch-delivery-service-that-would-vie-with-fedex-ups-1518175920">直到 2018 年</a>才开始认真运送自己的包裹，现已成为该国第三大托运商，运送了近 50 亿件包裹。但不是几乎所有）该公司去年的包裹。所有这些包裹都将发送给经过零售商培训的客户群，他们预计包裹会在短短几天内到达，这比以前的周转预期要快得多。<br><br>您可能只会注意到每周送到<em>您</em>家的包裹很少（平均家庭有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pitneybowes.com/content/dam/pitneybowes/us/en/shipping-index/22-pbcs-04529-2021-global-parcel-shipping-index-ebook-web-002.pdf">三到四个</a>）。但每次你收到一只时，同一天，全国还有超过 5000 万其他人刷新他们的跟踪信息，并检查他们的门铃摄像头，看看他们的新鞋或处方补充品是否也到了。这些包裹必须装载到一系列卡车上，开到一个地址，然后由人类运送到欢迎垫上。<br><br>用不间断的包裹消防水带喷洒美国，其后果对工人来说是艰难的，但我们其他人并不总是能看到。更多的包裹需要<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucks-roads-damage-traffic-supply-chain-11643210764">更多的卡车</a>在路上行驶，这意味着该国州际公路上有更多的半挂卡车，住宅区街道上有更多的超大型送货车辆，这使得每个人的交通状况都变得更糟。这些车辆给道路和桥梁带来巨大压力，需要更频繁的维修。主要为乘用车建造的街道可能太窄，或者转弯太紧，即使是最熟练的货运车辆司机也无法轻松驾驶，而且每年进行如此多的送货上门不可避免地会导致事故、车辆卡住和受伤。当真正需要送货时，这些道路往往没有方便卡车停放的地方，因此它们堵塞了街道并造成了更多的交通。而每个司机都要一遍又一遍地重复，每天几十次，直到全国每天数以千万计的包裹送完，数十万辆货运车都空了。<br><br>一旦包裹从卡车上卸下来，事情就不一定容易多了。在全国范围内，当地住房存量的中位年龄早于网上购物的广泛采用，这意味着大多数房屋都是在我们许多人在外出工作时每周多次收到送货服务之前建造的。邮箱大多还是原来的大小，所以司机需要把你的东西扔到你的门廊或灌木丛后面，并祈祷最好的结果。在公寓大楼里，光是进入就可能很困难，而且许多老房子没有足够大的邮件室来安全地存放所有东西。除非您住在豪华建筑中，否则您可能没有带有服务员的前台来代替您接收包裹。当一堆全新的、不安全的东西躺在周围时，其中一些<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2019/11/stealing-amazon-packages-age-nextdoor/598156/">肯定会被盗</a>，尽管假设盗窃可能会被误导：包裹体积如此之大，将它们全部送到正确的地方是一项如此复杂的工作，以至于许多丢失的包裹<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/02/nyregion/online-shopping-package-theft.html">只是误送</a>。<br><br>然而，该国主要托运人的送货人员规模的增长速度并没有跟上包裹数量的激增以及客户对运输时间的不断缩短的期望。许多航运公司雇佣了工资较低的兼职工人来填补空缺，而不是创造新的全职工作，亚马逊的很大一部分送货是由使用自己的车辆并按包裹支付报酬的零工工人完成的。<br><br>无论是否是零工，所有这些工作都在一年中的每一天进行，而且大部分是在室外，因此司机在变得更加极端的气候下处理更多的包裹并做更多的体力劳动，而且他们主要是在货运车辆中完成这些工作缺乏空调。 UPS 司机因高温而<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/20/business/ups-postal-workers-heat-stroke-deaths.html">在工作中死亡</a>，卡车司机和 UPS 之间的谈判中，送货车辆的空调成为主要症结所在。 （工会的新合同如果获得批准，将保证新的运输车辆配备空调，并为旧的运输车辆增加更好的通风。）<br><br>尽管如此，提高工资和提高安全性只是解决送货工人在如此快速地运送如此多包裹时所面临的更广泛问题的第一步。道路和桥梁安全的改善并不是政府预算中性感的项目，无论这些改善是否进行，卡车都会继续行驶。将科技公司强加给美国人的送货经济完全改造为日常生活的现实可能是不可能的。无论如何，托运人将继续尝试。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ups-strike-union-contract-package-deliveries/674864/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ups-strike-union-contract-package-deliveries/674864/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump’s Legal Turmoil Just Keeps Getting Worse]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>更糟糕的是<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/ZmVTDGZyYTnV7IDzF1gryy9M3zk=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/trump_1/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>斯科特·摩根/路透社</figcaption></figure><small><em>更新于 2023 年 7 月 28 日东部时间晚上 8:09</em></small><br><br>昨天，特别检察官杰克·史密斯在佛罗里达州联邦法院获得了针对唐纳德·特朗普及其助手沃尔廷·诺塔的机密文件案的替代起诉书。修订后的起诉书增加了一名新被告，海湖庄园的物业经理卡洛斯·德奥利维拉，以及两项新的妨碍司法罪名，罪名是试图“改变、销毁、毁坏或隐藏证据”。新指控源于特朗普、诺塔和德奥利维拉于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/now/video/trump-de-oliveira-and-nauta-allegedly-tried-to-delete-video-footage-at-mar-a-lago-189438533520">2022 年夏天</a>共同试图删除海湖庄园的监控录像的指控。据称，这一切都发生在联邦调查局试图归还特朗普从白宫拿走的大量机密文件的过程中，这一努力最终以政府于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/08/politics/mar-a-lago-search-warrant-fbi-donald-trump/index.html">8 月 8 日</a>对该地产执行搜查令告终。<br><br>取代起诉书还根据《间谍法》增加了一项新罪名，该罪名涉及一份被标记为<span class="smallcaps">绝密</span>并被确定为“有关外国军事活动的演示文稿”的文件，据描述，特朗普在贝德明斯特向没有安全许可的人挥手致意。新泽西州，俱乐部。它还指控德奥利维拉在被问及对海湖庄园存放和移动的箱子的了解时多次向联邦调查局撒谎。<br><br>此案对特朗普来说只会变得更加糟糕。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/trump-indictment/674345/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：这份起诉书是不同的</a><br><br>回想一下， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://d3i6fh83elv35t.cloudfront.net/static/2023/06/trump-indictment.pdf">最初的起诉书</a>称，2022 年 5 月，诺塔在特朗普的指示下从海湖庄园的“储藏室”移走了 64 箱文件。根据起诉书，Nauta 于 6 月 1 日又拆除了 11 个箱子。起诉书中复制了几张<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-indictment-pictures-photos-documents-boxes-mar-a-lago-bathroom/">照片</a>，描绘了一堆凌乱的盒子——其中一张附近有一台看起来像复印机的东西。新的阻碍指控涉及储藏室和附近的安全摄像头，在特朗普的律师<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-lawyer-christina-bobb-speaks-federal-investigators-mar-lago-case-rcna51459">于 6 月 3 日</a>向联邦调查局声称特朗普已归还他所拥有的所有物品后，这些摄像头可能拍摄到人们移动箱子的镜头。<br><br>替代起诉书称，特朗普于 6 月 22 日从律师<i>那里得知，他们正在等待大陪审团发出传票，要求出示“任何和所有监控记录、视频”，第二天</i>他就策划了一次销毁监控录像的尝试，但未获成功。来自内部摄像机的图像、照片和/或闭路电视”，包括来自“底层（地下室）”。 6月23日，特朗普致电德奥利维拉，与他进行了24分钟的交谈。传票于 6 月 24 日发出。当天，一名工作人员给贝德明斯特的诺塔发短信说特朗普想见他。不到两个小时，诺塔改变了前往伊利诺伊州的计划，转而前往海湖庄园。 6月25日，诺塔和德奥利维拉来到底层地下室，“用手电筒穿过储藏室所在的隧道，观察并指出监控摄像头”。<br><br> 6 月 27 日，在确认俱乐部的 IT 主管（起诉书中被称为“员工 4”）有空后，德奥利维拉与该人一起穿过地下室隧道，在那里他们进行了一场旨在“保持在两人之间的对话”。他们。”德奥利维拉告诉他，“‘老板’希望删除服务器。”员工 4 拒绝了，称他“无权这样做”。德奥利维拉回答道：“我们要做什么？”<br><br>起诉书称，当天晚些时候，诺塔和德奥利维拉“穿过海湖庄园北边的灌木丛会面”。大约两个小时后，特朗普给德奥利维拉打电话，“他们聊了大约三分半钟”。今年夏天晚些时候，即联邦调查局进行搜查两周后（7 月份获得了监控录像，8 月初发出了逮捕令），诺塔给特朗普的另一名员工打电话说：“有人只是想确保卡洛斯是个好人。” ”。该员工回应称，德奥利维拉对特朗普“忠诚”，特朗普“当天”给德奥利维拉打电话，并告诉他将为他找一名律师。<br><br>从这个叙述中可以看出一些事情，所有这些都对特朗普不利。试图删除视频片段的行为是对大陪审团针对视频片段的传票的直接回应，而不是出于预防性、例行公事、错误或其他非犯罪原因。对于证明妨碍司法罪而言，这是一件大事，而特朗普在销毁联邦大陪审团感兴趣的潜在定罪证据的努力中所扮演的角色和影响力是显而易见的。这一事实模式还支持了政府的论点，即特朗普诱导他人隐瞒和篡改证据的行为是“故意”和“故意”根据相关的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/1512">《美国法典》第 18 篇《美国法典》第 1512(b)(2) 条</a>规定进行的。 （新的《间谍法》指控也驳斥了特朗普对福克斯新闻主持人布雷特·拜尔的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow-show/maddowblog/classified-docs-case-trump-adds-bravado-claim-evolving-story-rcna91563">说法</a>，即他与缺乏安全许可的人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2023/06/26/donald-trump-audio-recording-iran-documents/">讨论</a>似乎是军事战争计划的录音中“本身不存在任何文件”。）与此同时，取代起诉书以一系列确凿证据为基础——根据起诉书，包括监控录像；多名员工的证词；以及关键人物之间的大量短信和电话记录，其中包括特朗普本人。<br><br>海湖庄园案是特朗普迄今为止面临的两起刑事审判之一——另一起是由曼哈顿地区检察官因涉嫌财务不当行为提起的——至少<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/trump-legal-issues-two-more-174329060.html">还有两起</a>可能即将发生，其中一起是因特朗普参与暴力事件而引发的。试图阻挠 2021 年 1 月 6 日总统权力的和平过渡，以及佐治亚州富尔顿县的另一起事件，因为他有记录地试图影响佐治亚州国务卿“找到”足够的选票，将该州纳入他的选举行列。在所有这些案件中，检察官的任务都是独一无二的，因为被告是美国前总统，也是 2024 年共和党提名的领跑者——这都是历史上的第一。曼哈顿和联邦法院的刑事陪审团必须达成一致，因此特朗普的法律团队只需要确保一名不会定罪的忠诚者。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：唐纳德·特朗普的“可怕消息”</a><br><br>这就是为什么新的妨碍司法指控背后的叙述如此引人注目，这一点很重要。这个故事让人想起英雄在神话和文学中的旅程，这一旅程由约瑟夫·坎贝尔 (Joseph Campbell) 于 1949 年首次阐述，并成为从<i>《指环王》</i>到<i>《哈利·波特》</i>等无数好莱坞大片的基础。在这个叙述中，第四号员工成为英雄，他拒绝了特朗普的邪恶冲动，然后挺身而出，自担风险。参与此案的检察官和执法官员已经<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aol.com/sports/prosecutors-trump-mar-lago-case-154859205.html">面临着</a>网上和面对面的严重威胁和骚扰。特朗普上周<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newsweek.com/donald-trump-deranged-jack-smith-election-interference-1814772">称</a>杰克·史密斯“精神错乱”。希望这个故事对于好人来说有一个美好的结局。<br><br><small><em>这篇文章最初指出，单个效忠者将导致无罪释放。事实上，这会导致陪审团悬而未决。</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 16:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/donald-trump-indictment-jack-smith/674855/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/donald-trump-indictment-jack-smith/674855/</item><item><title><![CDATA[Barbie Is Everything. Ken Is Everything Else.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>英雄。恶棍。因塞。战士。领导者。海滩。肯不是<em>芭比娃娃</em>电影的明星，但他是这部电影悲剧性的、可塑的心脏。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/foIKWTn7yxm9P-n6uFr3fcC8tII=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/ken_hr/original.jpg" alt="瑞恩·高斯林在《芭比娃娃》中饰演肯" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Jaap Buitendijk / 华纳兄弟影业</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i data-stringify-type="italic">》周一至周五</i><i data-stringify-type="italic">必读的一篇文章</i>。 <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br><strong><em>本文包含电影</em></strong><strong>《芭比娃娃》的剧透。</strong><br><br>本周早些时候，埃隆·马斯克宣布他将重塑自己的社交媒体平台：Twitter 现在简单来说就是 X。人们纷纷猜测为什么马斯克会用一个知名品牌来换取一封通常与拒绝和色情相关的信件： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-rebrand-paypall-x-sounded-like-porn-site-twitter-2023-7">尽管</a>， 或许。或者也许——这是最荒谬的理论，因此也是最有可能的——那个给自己的车型命名为“S”、“3”、“X”和“Y”的人再次这样做是为了哈哈。据员工<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/24/technology/twitter-x-elon-musk.html">报告</a>，Twitter 更名为 X 后不久，其总部的会议室就被重新命名。马斯克尚未解雇的员工现在可以在名为“s3Xy”的会议室中规划民主化对话的未来。<br><br>碰巧，《X》与<em>芭比娃娃</em>电影在同一个周末上映。这种巧合是雄辩的。毫无疑问， <em>《芭比娃娃》</em>是一部关于它的同名电影，也是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/">对不可能的女性气质的探索</a>。但这也是一部关于肯的电影——在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/">导演格蕾塔·葛韦格的演绎</a>中，肯摆脱了芭比平淡配饰的地位，成为……一个权力痴迷的男孩，决心把世界变成他的玩物。<em>芭比</em>积极的营销活动中的任何元素都无法买到一位 52 岁的科技巨头所创造的相关性，当他不快速行动和/或打破事物时， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musks-humor-jokes-over-years-titter-420-69-2023-4">他会通过寻找新的方式将“69”写入其中来取乐</a>。公共记录。<br><br>许多专家认为，美国人生活在老​​年人统治之下：我们有太多的领导人在尝到了权力的滋味，然后花了几十年的时间来巩固它，却拒绝将自己的战利品让给其他任何人。然而，更广泛的事实更为可悲，因为它涉及那些无法应对权力责任的领导人，他们将我们的未来视为他们的玩具。几周来，马斯克和马克·扎克伯格一直在引发<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/01/technology/elon-musk-mark-zuckerberg-cage-match.html">外界猜测</a>，他们将通过电视转播的笼式比赛来解决业务分歧。美国人把我们的核密码交给了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/10/infantilization-of-a-president/542613/">一个布里奥尼襁褓中的小孩</a>。我们很可能<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/trump-2024-election-republican-primary-nomination-opponents/673882/">会再做一次</a>。我们生活在鲁莽的男孩国王的奴役之中。没有哪个虚构人物比一个看起来像男人但以男孩顽皮的欢乐将自己强加于世界的洋娃娃更能体现这种情况的荒谬性和悲剧性。肯需要关注。他发脾气。他播下混乱的种子。他威胁到整个秩序。他是<em>芭比</em>世界的塑料核心，也是我们世界的讽刺。<br><br>据说，芭比乐园是一个充满幼稚梦想的地方，安全、快乐、贫瘠、粉红色。在玩偶的土地上，“女孩的力量”并不是一个明显的谎言。相反，它是唯一存在的真理——支撑每一个无墙梦想之家的脚手架。它不仅塑造了芭比娃娃的职业生活（芭比总统、芭比物理学家、芭比医生），还塑造了他们对自己所处世界的感觉。芭比娃娃们自信、自我实现，而且总体上都很高兴，当然她们是这样：她们从来没有理由不这样。在《芭比乐园》中，芭比娃娃喜欢提醒自己，每一天都是“有史以来最好的一天”。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/">阅读：芭比娃娃怎么了？</a><br><br>芭比乐园里有肯斯，但他们就像芭比娃娃本身一样，具有各种装饰性和多余性。肯一家住在哪里？他们开什么梦想之车？这样的问题毫无意义。在一个将财产视为个人成就感的代表的地方，肯一家似乎什么也没有。在一个将职业等同于身份的社会中，他们也没有明显的职业。不过，肯一家确实有一份工作：在芭比娃娃的闪亮表演中充当可靠的临时演员。当需要的时候，肯斯就会出现。他们很开朗。他们很有耐心。他们总是准备好穿上亮片，微笑着参加精心编排的舞蹈。与芭比乐园中的几乎所有其他东西一样，它们非常简单。因此，它们也非常无聊。<br><br>例外的是，对于其中一个：根据芭比乐园的二乘二逻辑，肯与刻板芭比配对。这个肯（由瑞恩·高斯林饰演）对自己的阶级地位感到不满。芭比乐园可能看起来像<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://collider.com/themyscira-wonder-woman-series-paradise-lost/">天堂岛</a>式的母系社会，亚马逊人高 11 英寸，由聚氯乙烯模制而成；然而，肯提醒我们乌托邦的残酷局限性。这部电影最明显的问题出现在早期，当刻板芭比（玛格特·罗比饰）发现自己受到人类状况的各种侮辱（不完美的棕色烤面包，死亡的想法，脂肪团）时。但早在芭比危机发生之前，芭比乐园的预制完美设施就并不完美。肯（Ken）首当其冲地犯了错误。他不仅仅是芭比娃娃的玩物；他也是芭比娃娃的玩物。他也是她随意残忍行为的接受者。 “你现在可以走了，”芭比告诉他，当他的脸垂下来时，她露出了微笑。后来：“我不想让你在这里。”<br><br>正是这些台词让<em>《芭比娃娃》</em>在上映后的几天里，遭到了一些对男性仇恨、性别歧视和“有毒女性气质”的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2023/07/24/if-i-made-a-movie-that-treated-women-the-way-barbie-treats-men-feminists-would-want-me-executed/">愤怒</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tmz.com/2023/07/22/barbie-attacked-right-wingers-anti-man-feminist-trash/">指控</a>。然而，这些批评忽略了——或者可能忽略了——即使在一部关于玩具的电影中也可能存在讽刺。芭比乐园的动态既复杂又简单：芭比在其范围内与世隔绝，在现实世界中代表了父权制的受益者。肯本质上代表了其他所有人。芭比对肯的不屑一顾，并不是刻薄的意思；而是她的意思。她对待他不假思索，因为她从来没有考虑过这些话——或者任何事情——可能会造成伤害。她从来不需要这样做。无论在她的社会还是在我们的社会，舒适都是一种奢侈。对于那些无法想象他人痛苦的人来说，人类世界的口号——以及将幼儿园课程中的善良和同理心转变为政治诉求的惨淡动态——毫无意义。<br><br>不过，它们对肯来说很有意义。在影片一开始，他就是这个塑料世界中最混乱的人类特征，是需求和希望的纠缠，最终是愤怒。在笑容满面的土地上，他皱起了眉头。被无尽的欢乐包围着，他感到疼痛。他感觉到有些事情非常不对劲。但他能做的就是感知。芭比乐园可能有总统、宪法和最高法院，但实际上它是非常非政治的。 （政治是对人类和冲突的回应；芭比乐园两者都不允许。）因此，没有语言或发泄他的挫败感——你可能会说，被一个<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/the-feminine-mystique-anniversary-betty-friedan/8751751?ean=9780393934656&amp;ref=&amp;source=IndieBound&amp;title=The+Feminine+Mystique%3A+A+Norton+Critical+Edition+%28Norton+Critical+Editions%29">没有名字的问题所困扰</a>——肯只是摸索着度过他的困境。他的渴望让他受到了芭比乐园中陌生的东西的困扰：脆弱。<br><br><em>芭比</em>的魔力很大程度上归功于罗比和高斯林，以及他们作为演员将塑料与人类、真诚与阵营融为一体的能力。罗比的表演就其本身而言，是一个升华的问题。它捕捉到了使芭比娃娃成为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/05/tiny-shoulders-review-hulu/559277/">经久不衰的偶像和无尽争议的</a>许多元素，其中包括她难以企及的美丽、她快乐的天真、她的白皙、她的苗条，以及她提醒人们， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/08/jeffrey-epstein-and-the-myth-of-the-underage-woman/596140/">即使是孩子也会受到女性不断变化的需求的困扰。</a> 。高斯林也发现了类似的细微差别，但方向相反：臭名昭著的是，肯是一个因缺席而被定义为加号的人。高斯林填补了这个空白。为此，他将娃娃的一种基本讽刺元素——芭比和肯是经常被误认为成年人的青少年——融入到他的表演中。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/08/jeffrey-epstein-and-the-myth-of-the-underage-woman/596140/">阅读：“未成年女性”的神话</a><br><br>在高斯林的笔下，肯生活在各种情绪之中，而这些情绪总是超出他的控制范围。他时而暴躁，时而充满可能性，时而冲动，时而自我意识。这也意味着，这个尖嘴娃娃在很多方面都是一个非常典型的青少年。 Barbie, newly beset by human-borne feeling, shocks herself by crying—first a single tear, and then a flood of them. Gosling&#39;s Ken cries too. But his discord has a stereotypically masculine edge. He erupts into anger. He feels entitled to sex, despite and because of his ignorance of it. He cares, deeply, what the other guys think of him. “You can&#39;t make me look uncool in front of Ken!” he wails at Barbie, panic flashing in his eyes.<br><br> Ken, in the film&#39;s early scenes, takes his tumult out on Barbie. There he is, radiating look-at-me longing. There he is, like Romeo with his poems or <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1GoH3M9Kb4g">Lloyd Dobler with his boom box</a> , turning love into a show. He orients his life around Barbie so thoroughly that, before long, he is becoming the one thing a Ken must not be in Barbie Land: a hindrance.<br><br> Ken resents his neediness as much as Barbie does. But Barbie Land offers him no other option. <em>She is everything; he&#39;s just Ken</em> . That is the way of this world. Gosling&#39;s performance channels all of that. And then, powerfully, it escalates the matter: Ken&#39;s need for Barbie becomes so consuming that it curdles into violence. Soon, his hopeful smiles are twisting into sneers. The stubbornness of his desire for Barbie—and his inability to accept her disinterest—begins to evoke the grim entitlements of the incel. His plight becomes everyone else&#39;s threat.<br><br> It&#39;s unsettling, the doll made dangerous. That&#39;s what makes it so effective. The bulk of the film finds Barbie and Ken on a journey that mimics adolescence: Having left the land of protection and play and easy dreams, they are plunged into the realities of the human world—and the hard transactions of adulthood. The dolls must navigate a place that has no shortage of language for its political condition: <em>patriarchy</em> , <em>marginalization</em> , <em>objectification</em> , <em>oppression</em> .<br><br> Ken loves it. Walking on a street in LA—clothed, through an accident of circumstance in the plot and inspired costuming choices beyond it, in fringe-covered Western wear—he begins to strut. He feels, for the first time, respected, admired, seen. Barbie, meanwhile, is the one made to feel—and then to fear—the vulnerabilities of her gender. One of <em>Barbie</em> ’s best jokes finds Ken, having returned to Barbie Land, playing her a song on his guitar—singing not <em>to</em> Barbie, he makes clear, but <em>at</em> her. Ken croons and crows, entranced by the romance of his gesture, holding Barbie&#39;s gaze and refusing to let it go. The absurdity of it all is punctured by the lyrics of the song he chooses—one that became, in the real world, a hit: <em>I wanna push you around, well I will, well I will / I wanna push you down, well I will, well I will</em> …<br><br> Adolescence is a time of extremes. And Ken, having experienced manhood in a man&#39;s world, reacts to his new situation with juvenile glee. Soaking up his surroundings as a child might—alive, always, to the images and messages around him—he intuits first that manliness is everything in the real world, and second, that manliness must involve horses. (Patriarchy, he concludes, is the system “where men on horses run everything.”) He is entranced by images of Rocky Balboa and Bill Clinton, captivated by the guys who high-five one another at the gym. Back in Barbie Land, importing the lessons he&#39;s learned from reality, he takes over Barbie&#39;s Dream House. His Mojo Dojo Casa House is a bachelor pad and a bar and, in its overall aesthetic, a tribute to John Wayne&#39;s influence on American tropes of masculinity. Its decor features, obviously, an abundance of horses.<br><br> Ken&#39;s excesses are funny, and foolish, and, except for the house-stealing stuff, pretty relatable. Like any teenager, Ken is figuring out who he is, and trying the world&#39;s possibilities on for size. But his immaturity is not contained, and this is its problem. His adolescent approach to the world, instead, inflicts itself on everyone else. Soon—a plot twist that, for anyone who has followed US politics in recent years, doubles as a twist of the knife—Ken is trying to rewrite Barbie Land&#39;s constitution.<br><br> There&#39;s an ominous kind of justice to Ken&#39;s attempts to inject himself into the political life of Barbie Land. It is a zero-sum solution to the problems of a zero-sum world. The Ken doll has been called, over the years, a “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/22/style/ken-barbie-doll-biography-cec/index.html">drip with seriously abridged genitalia</a> ,” “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/a44285254/the-history-of-ken-barbie/">an uncomfortably freighted icon of anti-masculinity</a> ,” and—by Gosling, during <em>Barbie</em> ’s promotional tour—“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/07/22/entertainment/ryan-gosling-ken-barbie-doll-cec/index.html">an accessory, and not even one of the cool ones</a> .” When Ken was featured in 2010&#39;s <em>Toy Story 3</em> , he found himself on the receiving end of the following line: “You ascot-wearing pink-noser! You&#39;re not a toy … You&#39;re a purse with legs!”<br><br> The insult was made all the more insulting because it was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A-H9-CLfOWg">delivered</a> by a tuber with detachable limbs and anger-management issues. But Mr. Potato Head was simply saying what everyone already knew: The defining fact of Ken is that Ken is defined by Barbie. That alone makes it hard not to feel bad for the guy. And for many of <em>Barbie</em> ’s viewers, his plight may feel extremely familiar. A key moment in the film, as my colleague Shirley Li <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">wrote</a> , comes from one of its human protagonists, Gloria (America Ferrera), who summons a life&#39;s worth of frustration into a speech about the challenges—and the utter irrationality—of being a woman in a world shaped by men. Another key moment, though, comes from Ken. It&#39;s near the end of the movie, and he&#39;s finally getting the one thing he&#39;s really wanted: Barbie is listening to him. He&#39;s telling her what it&#39;s like to be dimmed so that somebody else might shine. And then he adds the kicker: “It doesn&#39;t feel good, does it?”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">Read: The surprising key to understanding the</a> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/"><em>Barbie</em></a> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">film</a><br><br> The critics who have accused <em>Barbie</em> of misandry might want to watch that moment, if indeed they ever watched it at all, once more. Ken&#39;s line gives punctuation, effectively, to Gloria&#39;s speech. And it does what our current political slogans beg us, fruitlessly, to do: It empathizes. Ken doesn&#39;t really want political power, he discovers; it&#39;s a lot of work. (Plus, disappointingly, horses are merely “men-extenders.”) What he really seeks is the power to figure out who he is on his own terms. Does Ken want Barbie at all? Would he, as the film hints, rather be paired with another Ken? What would he choose to be were his identity broader than Barbie and Beach?<br><br> Ken is, by the end of the film, not merely a doll who has known life in the human world; he is also a guy who understands what it&#39;s like to be treated as an extra in someone else&#39;s story. In him, the debates that shape—and limit—our political possibilities become elegantly straightforward. Ken is a person who is denied the full dignity of his personhood. That—whatever your worldview, whatever your particular circumstance, whatever your feelings about the word <em>patriarchy</em> —is a blatant form of injustice.<br><br> But Ken is also, at the story&#39;s conclusion, a guy who has escaped from his arrested development. He has come to embody one of <em>Barbie</em> ’s core ideas: that patriarchy is a profound form of immaturity. It causes childishness. It results from it too. Here is one reason for hope, though, as our very real men-children keep trying to remake the world into their Mojo Dojo Casa House: For Ken, immaturity becomes what it is for most people—a phase on the way to something better. Ken doesn&#39;t become human. He does, however, grow up.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 13:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[American Family Life Should Not Be This Volatile]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Welcome to the age of tremors. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/svoxez6gbJG4KFeL--3BSnqxm9s=/0x0:3333x4166/648x810/media/img/2023/07/27/MG179418_copy/original.jpg" alt="一个男人俯身在他的孩子身上的剪影" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Gueorgui Pinkhassov / Magnum</figcaption></figure> <span class="smallcaps">Parenthood has always involved unpredictability</span> : wake-ups at 2 am, calls from school, the dreaded words <em>my stomach hurts</em> .这种日常差异通常源于生病或受惊的孩子，并且是家庭生活基本动态的一部分。然而，今天的美国父母也面临着日益严重的外部干扰和旨在提供稳定的机构的退化。其结果是，许多家庭经常会因为一些问题而陷入困境，这些问题不仅仅是不方便，但还不是灾难性的。这会滋生父母的压力、不安全感和疲惫。简而言之，美国人已经进入了一个颤抖的时代。<br><br>过去半个世纪以来，这个国家一直在走这条道路。从 20 世纪 70 年代开始，一系列经济和社会政策决策导致了政治学家雅各布·哈克 (Jacob Hacker) 所说的从政府和企业到家庭的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-great-risk-shift-the-new-economic-insecurity-and-the-decline-of-the-american-dream-jacob-s-hacker/9780190844141?affiliate_id=atl-347">“巨大风险转移”</a> 。 Hacker&#39;s idea mainly refers to economic changes, such as the private sector&#39;s shift from guaranteed pensions to stock-market-dependent 401(k)s. But this notion of a “DIY society” can extend to the numerous ways parents—especially mothers—are asked to “hold it all together,” the University of Wisconsin at Madison sociologist Jessica Calarco told me. For example, the rise of double-earner households was not met with policies like affordable child care or mandatory paid leave. Instead, families have been forced to navigate confusing and competitive marketplaces to acquire basic services such as day care and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/01/summer-day-camps-activities-childcare/672837/">summer camp</a> , and they are largely on their own to deal with any breakdowns.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/06/us-paid-parental-leave-child-welfare-tax-credit/661276/">Read: The US leaves parents on their own for a reason</a><br><br> What&#39;s new in the 2020s is that these breakdowns are occurring more frequently. Consider the series of challenges families have faced in recent years. There has been a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/17/health/formula-shortage-one-year-later/index.html">terrible shortage of infant formula</a> , as well as children&#39;s medicines such as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/01/05/why-childrens-tylenol-shortage">Tylenol</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aap.org/en/pages/amoxicillin-shortage-antibiotic-options-for-common-pediatric-conditions/">amoxicillin</a> , and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/students-struggle-academically-fight-in-schools-amid-adderall-shortage-209d01e0">Adderall</a> . Child care has become even <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/07/us-childcare-programs-expensive-underfunded/670927/">scarcer and more expensive</a> —and, because of staffing shortages, programs regularly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kcrg.com/2023/07/25/families-hunt-new-child-care-after-iowa-city-facility-suddenly-closes/">close</a> or reduce hours <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://vtdigger.org/2022/08/02/closure-of-a-child-care-center-in-essex-junction-sends-families-scrambling-for-options/">with little notice</a> . Extreme heat has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/01/us/michgan-schools-heat.html">forced school closures</a> ; wildfire smoke from Canada has caused some US <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2023/07/23/summer-camp-canada-wildfire-smoke/">summer camps</a> to delay their start times.<br><br> Some of this volatility is because of climate change, public-policy decisions, or corporate-profit maximizing. Some of it is the result of multiple factors. The infant-formula crisis was caused mainly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/doj-investigating-abbott-plant-at-the-center-of-2022-baby-formula-shortage#:~:text=The%20factory's%20closure%20in%20February,banks%2C%20friends%20and%20doctor's%20offices.">by a single factory shutting down, a predicament foreshadowed by</a> policy makers enabling a handful of companies to control <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pbs.org/newshour/economy/the-current-baby-formula-shortage-sheds-light-on-longstanding-weaknesses-within-the-industry">nearly the entire market</a> . Additionally, as the labor economist Aaron Sojourner told me, there has been a significant rise of “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.demos.org/sites/default/files/publications/Scheduling_Hourly_Workers_Demos.pdf">just-in-time scheduling</a> ”—a model where businesses operate with the barest minimum of employees who can be called in or sent home on very short notice—in low-wage industries including retail, food service, and call centers. This leads to instability in the lives of workers, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rsfjournal.org/content/8/5/24.abstract">especially parents</a> , and increases the risk of something going awry for customers if a sole employee quits or cannot make their shift. Yet <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hrdive.com/news/a-running-list-of-states-and-localities-with-predictive-scheduling-mandates/540835/">only one state and a few cities</a> have laws limiting just-in-time scheduling.<br><br> At the same time, decades of neglect are causing public systems to break down. A lack of adequate funding and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/recoding-america-why-government-is-failing-in-the-digital-age-and-how-we-can-do-better-jennifer-pahlka/9781250266774?affiliate_id=atl-347">modernized processes</a> has led to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.baltimorebrew.com/2023/07/18/three-public-pools-have-yet-to-open-in-baltimore-hanging-residents-out-to-dry/">decaying public services</a> and hollowed-out government offices with poor responsiveness. Applications for child-care assistance <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kcur.org/politics-elections-and-government/2023-05-10/missouri-families-cant-get-help-affording-child-care-because-of-bureaucratic-hurdles">can be a nightmare to complete</a> , and even well-resourced states like New York and Illinois have recently had major problems getting <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://wgntv.com/news/illinois/some-childcare-providers-forced-to-close-after-not-getting-paychecks-from-state/">timely payments to child-care providers</a> . Parents of children with disabilities are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnet.com/personal-finance/social-security-disability-claims-wait-record-high-how-to-avoid-delays/">facing down</a> record-long application-processing times and extremely limited support staff.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">The age of tremors helps explain</span> a seemingly odd disconnect between people&#39;s perceptions of their personal lives and of the way the country is going. <em>The Atlantic</em> ’s Derek Thompson <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2022/06/american-economy-negative-perception-inflation/661149/">described this phenomenon</a> as “Everything is terrible, but I&#39;m fine,” pointing to the tension between contemporary indicators such as healthy disposable income and a sense of economic gloom. For many parents, I might extend the description to “Everything is terrible; I&#39;m holding on, but what&#39;s going to go wrong next?”<br><br> Psychologists are clear that a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://psychcentral.com/stress/stress-and-the-concept-of-control">reasonable sense of control</a> is a key component of mental health. Having to worry about Canadian wind directions or scouring a half dozen stores for medicine to bring down your child&#39;s fever are not only practical pain points; they foster a general atmosphere of instability. Some parents of young children <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/17/health/formula-shortage-one-year-later/index.html">still reported lingering fear and anxiety</a> about formula supply after shelves were filled again.<br><br> Such constant precarity takes an emotional toll regardless of one&#39;s bank account. Research shows <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapediatrics/fullarticle/2789946">significant declines in parents&#39; mental health</a> since before the pandemic, and recent years have brought <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/05/well/family/parental-burnout-symptoms.html">high levels of parental exhaustion and burnout</a> , as well as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsroom.thecignagroup.com/loneliness-epidemic-persists-post-pandemic-look">loneliness</a> . About three-quarters of parents are very or somewhat concerned that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.capita.org/thinkofthechildren">climate change will harm their children</a> or other young children they know. This stress and insecurity can easily <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Tumbleweed-Society-Working-Caring-Insecurity/dp/0199957711?asin=0199957711&amp;revisionId=&amp;format=4&amp;depth=1">trickle down</a> to the whole family.<br><br> A simple rejoinder is that none of this is new. Parents a century ago could not count on antibiotics because they were not commercially available. But consider the more recent past: Today&#39;s parents have less predictability than those in the last quarter of the 20th century. As the Stanford sociologist Marianne Cooper wrote in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/cut-adrift-families-in-insecure-times-marianne-cooper/9780520277670?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>Cut Adrift: Families in Insecure Times</em></a> , the trends that began at the time of the great risk shift brought about substantial increases in income and job instability by the 2000s.<br><br> Moreover, until the past few decades, social institutions and bonds have been better prepared to stand in the gap. Labor unions, fraternal associations, and especially <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/28/opinion/religion-affiliation-community.html">faith communities</a> provide not merely a sense of connectivity but also material support such as meals after a birth or trusted people who can watch the kids in a pinch. These networks have been experiencing a steady decline in membership.<br><br> A permanent age of tremors is not, however, inevitable. Policy makers can both stabilize the ground and help families deal with the quakes. The first step is making healthy, predictable family life a policy priority. Laws that strengthen the child-care system, provide robust paid leave, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fortune.com/2023/04/17/irs-phone-wait-times-taxes/">reinvest in public services</a> and lower <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2021/07/how-government-learned-waste-your-time-tax/619568/">their administrative burdens</a> , and restrict just-in-time scheduling are all ways to shift risks from families back onto government and corporations. As a guiding principle, policy makers should reduce chaos, liberating parents and children to deepen their connections to one another and their community.<br><br> Perhaps the saddest thing about the status quo is that this should be an age of wonders for families. We live in an era when modern medicine has eliminated many childhood diseases and is regularly developing new <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/fda-approves-rsv-injection-infants-rcna94698">treatments</a> . There has been a resurgence of interest in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/07/raising-kid-american-city/661506/">developing child-friendly communities</a> that can withstand climate disruption by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tpl.org/parks-address-climate-change-report">expanding and upgrading parks</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/2023/06/30/future-of-the-playground/">creating more natural playgrounds</a> . Technological tools make connecting with loved ones in far-flung parts of the country easier than ever. Parents could have so much to enjoy and look forward to—if they weren&#39;t constantly bracing for the next shake.<br><br> <small><em>​​When you buy a book using a link on this page, we receive a commission. Thank you for supporting</em> The Atlantic <em>.</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 14:15:02 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/parenting-challenges-american-families-child-care/674839/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/parenting-challenges-american-families-child-care/674839/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Are You Plagued by the Feeling That Everyone Used to Be Nicer?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Don&#39;t succumb. It&#39;s a psychological illusion. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/GW_aY81Q6JVAd2ooOzHsyY0N5EM=/0x0:4796x2698/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/radio_atlantic_2/original.jpg" alt="Image of two young women and one young man carrying a trash can together down a neighborhood sidewalk." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Len Trievnor / Hulton Archive / Getty</figcaption></figure> I have a long-running argument with my brother. He insists that his children, who are growing up in New York City right now, are a lot less safe than we were as kids in the same neighborhood. I happen to know this is absurd, and I&#39;ve tried for many years to convince him. I&#39;ve shown him news reports, crime statistics. Once I even downloaded an FBI report showing without a doubt that New York was much more dangerous 30 years ago. But he is unmoved. He remembers our childhood as gentler, safer. And I have to admit—there are moments when I walk around my old neighborhood and see visions of the mailman tipping his hat to my 10-year-old self, and the neighbors smiling as I made my way home to dinner.<br><br> Why do so many of us have this feeling that when we were younger, people were nicer and more moral, and took care of one another better? An experimental psychologist named Adam Mastroianni had also been wondering about this persistent conviction and did a systematic study of the phenomenon recently published in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06137-x"><em>Nature</em></a> .<br><br> Mastroianni documents that this hazy memory is shared by many different demographics, and felt quite strongly. He explains how the illusion works and why it has such a hold on us. And most important, he explains how it can distort not just our personal relationships but our culture and politics. In this episode of <em>Radio Atlantic</em> , I talk with Mastroianni and staff writer Julie Beck about the illusion of moral decline, and why it persists so strongly.<br><br> <em>W</em> <em>henever politicians or aspiring politicians make the claim that, you know, “Things used to be better, put me in charge and I&#39;ll make them better again”—that&#39;s a very old thing that we&#39;ve heard many times. And it resonates with us, perhaps because we are primed to believe it, even when it&#39;s not true.</em><br><br> Listen to the conversation here: <br><br><iframe class="lazyload" data-src="https://player.megaphone.fm/ATL9319336197" frameborder="no" height="200" scrolling="no" title="embedded interactive content" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <em>Subscribe here:</em> <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/radio-atlantic/id1258635512"><em>Apple Podcasts</em></a> <em>|</em> <a href="https://open.spotify.com/playlist/4PgNKjRJJWlaV6zuNr69BO"><em>Spotify</em></a> <em>|</em> <a href="https://www.stitcher.com/show/radio-atlantic"><em>Stitcher</em></a> <em>|</em> <a href="https://podcasts.google.com/feed/aHR0cHM6Ly9mZWVkcy5tZWdhcGhvbmUuZm0vcmFkaW9hdGxhbnRpYw"><em>Google Podcasts</em></a> <em>|</em> <a href="https://pca.st/ccxU"><em>Pocket Casts</em></a> <strong><em>The following episode transcript has been edited lightly for clarity:</em></strong><br><br> <strong>Hanna Rosin:</strong> So, Julie, you know—even though I get annoyed when other people say people used to be nicer, I kind of think I might feel that way too.<br><br> If I have a vision of my childhood and I&#39;m walking down the street from the playground, I imagine all my neighbors saying, “Hi, little Hanna.” [ <em>Laughter</em> .] And the mailman coming by, you know, and tipping his hat at me, and the old man walking his dog.<br><br> And, you know, I have no idea if this memory is accurate, but I definitely have that feeling that people were nicer.<br><br> <strong>Julie Beck:</strong> Did you grow up in <em>Mister Rogers&#39; Neighborhood</em> ? Or what was it?<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> No; I actually grew up in Queens, New York. So it&#39;s probably, certainly not true. [ <em>Laughter.</em> ]<br><br> This is <em>Radio Atlantic</em> . I&#39;m Hanna Rosin. I invited my colleague Julie Beck on to talk about something that&#39;s always really bothered me. It&#39;s when people talk about how things are so much worse today than they were in the past.<br><br> And they say things like “Neighbors used to be nicer, and everyone used to smile at you and help you out.” And sometimes it&#39;s just grandpa chatter and you can pretty much ignore it. And then other times it turns into this “back when men were men and women were women”–type thing, which is more annoying.<br><br> <strong><em>Beck:</em></strong> <em>There&#39;s a benign wish to, like, tip your hat to the mailman. And then there&#39;s a “Oh, we need to bring back the social order of the 1950s.” And then you&#39;re like, “Whoa, how did we end up here?”</em><br><br> Julie analyzes psychological research and social trends, and she&#39;s also the host of another Atlantic podcast, <em>How to Talk to People</em> .<br><br> And she&#39;s here to help me understand this very interesting research that just emerged about this strong conviction people have that everything has gotten worse.<br><br> <strong><em>Adam Mastroianni</em></strong> <strong>:</strong> <em>So my whole life, I&#39;ve heard people say things like, “You used to be able to keep your doors unlocked at night,” or “You can&#39;t trust someone&#39;s word anymore.”</em><br><br> <em>And I always chafed at those kinds of statements. So part of it was wanting to prove everybody wrong. But part of it, too, was like,</em> Well, if they&#39;re right, this is a big problem. <em>And that&#39;s kind of where we got started.</em><br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> That is Adam Mastroianni. He recently published a paper in <em>Nature</em> called “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.experimental-history.com/p/the-illusion-of-moral-decline">The Illusion of Moral Decline</a> .” Adam is a psychologist, and he&#39;s the author of the science blog <em>Experimental History.</em> And he spent a decade systematically studying why we feel things were better in the past … and what it means.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> I think my first year of graduate school was when Trump got elected. And so obviously it was a moment of “Make America Great Again” being sort of the vibe of the day.<br><br> Seeing claims that “The past was good, the present is bad, put me in charge and I can bring the good past back” also just made me see how this is much more than, you know, uncles and brothers-in-law and people on the internet saying these things— that these claims resonate with people, and they help put people in the Oval Office.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yeah. I mean, I have to say, that&#39;s my motivation for being interested in your research, because I have always had a kind of detached curiosity about why this line resonates so strongly.<br><br> Like, why is it that—and it&#39;s not just American leaders, it&#39;s leaders all over the world—they can just say, “Oh, things were better back then,” and it immediately clicks for people? Like, they don&#39;t even have to explain it. You can just say, “You know, make America great again.” It&#39;s like four words, and all the assumptions are immediately there for people.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. When I give talks in an academic context about this paper, what I start with is the end of Trump&#39;s inaugural speech, where he says, “You know, we&#39;ll make America wealthy again and proud again and safe again and great again.” And I point out that the most important word in those sentences isn&#39;t <em>America</em> or <em>safe</em> or <em>proud</em> or <em>strong</em> or <em>great</em> . It&#39;s <em>again</em> .<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yes!<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Just that word does a ton of work. Which is that: Well, if things used to be great but aren&#39;t now, it means something changed. It implies that we can change it back. It evokes a sense of loss, but also a sense of possibility of restoring the loss.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yeah. And it is the word <em>again</em> . It&#39;s like that one little word sort of resolves something emotionally for people. It&#39;s hard to understand exactly how it works, but you say the word <em>again</em> , and everyone&#39;s like, “Ah, you just filled a hole for me.” You know? What exactly do you mean when you say “moral decline,” and why, if it&#39;s an illusion, does it feel so real?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> There are a few totally reasonable hypotheses about what people might think of when they talk about moral decline. It might be that everyone means, like, “I heard that the 1950s were a really good time. And so what I&#39;m really telling you is things have declined since then.” Not that they got worse in the past 10 years; that they got worse, you know, 20 years ago or 50 years ago. And we&#39;re just living in the bad times now.<br><br> In a later study, we asked people go back even further than that. “What about 20 years before that? What about 40 years before that?” And what they told us there is—“Before I arrived, nothing was happening. Things were good. Then I got born, and then things started to go downhill.”<br><br> And what&#39;s especially interesting is: It doesn&#39;t matter when you were born. So the people who were 30 told us it happened 30 years ago. The people who were 60 told us it happened 60 years ago.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Wait, really? So literally, people think the decline began when they came on this earth?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. So, I mean, we don&#39;t ask, like, the day before or the day after. But the question that we asked was: “Rate how kind, honest, nice, and good people are today. What about the year in which you were 20?” And people told us it was better then.<br><br> “What about the year in which you were born?” And people told us it was even better then. And then we asked, “What about 20 years before that? And 40 years before that?”<br><br> And there&#39;s no difference in people&#39;s answers. That line is flat. It&#39;s only when we asked about “20 years after your birth” that the line goes down.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> That is so interesting. I don&#39;t think I fully grasped that. So people are projecting whatever personal difficulties or struggles of life—now maybe I&#39;m extrapolating—onto the whole of humanity, like they&#39;re protecting their own life span onto a historical, broader cultural, political life span.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. And I mean, this is a bias of people&#39;s memory, because you don&#39;t have memories from before you were born. You do have memories from most of the time after you were born.<br><br> So it would make sense—if this is a memory bias—that it turns on sometime near the moment of your birth. Obviously not exactly then, but this would explain why we don&#39;t see this for what people think about before they were born and after.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Does it really not matter how young you are? The stereotype is obviously, you know, Grandpa Simpson. It&#39;s like, older people are always talking about how things were better back then, but not necessarily younger people.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah; we totally expected to find that as well, and we didn&#39;t really. So when you ask people about the decline that they have perceived over their lifetimes, there&#39;s no difference in the decline that younger and older people perceive.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Julie, I was surprised to hear that there wasn&#39;t a difference between older people and younger people in terms of how they perceive this moral decline. I mean, you&#39;re not an old person; you&#39;re young. So do you remember ever having this feeling?<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> I distinctly remember I did not get a smartphone until I moved to DC in 2013. So in the years before that, when I lived in Chicago, I have a memory of having so many more interactions with strangers on the street.<br><br> And I definitely do not have those nearly as frequently anymore. And I think it&#39;s just because we&#39;re all looking at our phones, right? So part of me kind of romanticizes the, you know, chance encounters of the pre-smartphone era and all of that.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yeah. And when I hear you say that, I&#39;m like, <em>Oh, it&#39;s fine for Julie to have that feeling, and it&#39;s fine for me to have that feeling.</em> But if I multiply it by a few million times, then I get this political movement of “Let&#39;s go back to the era when things were better,” and that I don&#39;t really like so much.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah. One thing that this makes me think of, too, is a line of research that has found that social trust has actually been declining in the US for decades. So people are essentially less and less likely to say that generally most other people can be trusted.<br><br> And so you&#39;re totally right that there are really big political implications for thinking the past was better and people used to be more trustworthy.<br><br> For me, it feels like kind of a chicken-or-an-egg question. Like, do we trust people less because we believe they&#39;ve gotten morally worse? Or do we believe people are worse because we&#39;re more disconnected from our communities?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> We focused here on a pretty narrow question, which is, “Has the way that people treat one another in their everyday lives changed over time?” And do people think that it has?<br><br> This is a model of when things are bad, it&#39;s easy for them to seem like they have gotten worse. And so I don&#39;t think this is the only domain where we might find this illusion, because people say this about a lot of different parts of life.<br><br> You know: that art is worse than it used to be. That culture is worse than it used to be. That the education system is worse than it used to be. But it seems pretty clear to me that we are predisposed to believe that it&#39;s true, even when it&#39;s not.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Your assumptions in this research are—people have this idea that a certain kind of morality has declined. But in your mind, it has not declined. So to you, this is like an illusion. I mean, you call it an illusion.正确的？<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yes.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Okay. So working within that assumption, what&#39;s your explanation? Like, why would a majority of us be operating under a delusion/illusion? Like something that <em>you&#39;re</em> saying is clearly not true.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> We think that there are two cognitive biases that can combine to produce this illusion. So this explanation has two parts. The first is what we call biased exposure, which is that people tend to attend to predominantly negative information, especially about people that they don&#39;t know.<br><br> So this is both a combination of the information that they receive about people that they don&#39;t know, which is primarily negative, and the information that they pay attention to. So this is why when you look out at the world beyond your personal world, it looks like it&#39;s full of people who are doing bad things. They&#39;re lying and cheating and stealing and killing.<br><br> The second part of the explanation is what we call biased memory. Memory researchers have noticed that the badness of bad memories tends to fade faster than the goodness of good memories.<br><br> So if you got turned down for your high-school prom, it feels pretty bad at the time. Twenty years later, it&#39;s maybe a funny story. If you have a great high-school prom, it feels pretty good at the time. And 20 years later, it&#39;s still a pretty nice memory. It doesn&#39;t feel as nice as it did to experience it, but it still feels pretty nice.<br><br> And that turns out to be, on average, what happens to people&#39;s memories: that the bad ones inch toward neutral faster than the good ones do, And the bad ones are more likely to both be forgotten and to become good in retrospect.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> So when I read the paper, Hanna, I wondered whether what might be going on is that people are, to some degree, picking up on a real change in the world.<br><br> There&#39;s the decline of social trust—but also widespread loneliness and disconnection and the erosion of community life, in the sense of fewer people knowing their neighbors and declining membership in community organizations.<br><br> And all of those things definitely have an impact on people&#39;s personal lives. But I think it manifests as a vague feeling like, <em>Oh, it&#39;s just harder to make friends or harder to feel like I&#39;m a part of my community.</em><br><br> So I wonder if we&#39;re feeling this sort of vague and troubling sense of disconnection and assigning it a false explanation: that things used to be better before, and people just suck more than they used to.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Oh, that&#39;s really interesting. So what you&#39;re saying is the feeling is real. Like, the feeling that something has changed is real because something <em>has</em> changed. There is more disconnection and loneliness.<br><br> So instead we make up this very tidy story. Like, “When I was a kid, things were better and people were nicer and the mailman tipped his hat”—and we just kind of stopped there.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah; there definitely are real things that are really happening that would make people feel disconnected from strangers around them. And I wonder if, yeah, we just have a hard time psychologically, knowing why that&#39;s the case.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> So Adam, I want to run a couple of theories by you. One is the possibility that something has actually changed. And we&#39;re just calling it by the wrong name. That, like, something has declined. And this is from a different body of psychological research about social trust.<br><br> That there is a change in our isolation, our sense of connectedness, our face-to-ace contact. Like there are some societal changes which are real and structural and have kind of left a hole in us that we are misnaming <em>morality</em> .<br><br> When we read it here, we thought there are some things that are changing and that do leave us a little despairing—and maybe we&#39;re just calling them by the wrong name.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Like we have this incredibly powerful feeling that something is wrong, and that “something” is connectedness or community or something like that.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. So it&#39;s very easy to slip from “People are less kind than they used to be” to <em>“Things</em> are worse than they used to be.” And so it is true that trust in institutions has declined over time. A lot of people also say that interpersonal trust has declined over time. And I actually think that case is much more overstated than the decline in institutional trust.<br><br> There&#39;s some work by a guy named Richard Eibach on how people think the world has gotten more dangerous. And he finds that people believe this. And the people who believe this, especially, are parents. And when you ask those parents “When did the world become more dangerous?,” you get a date that is curiously close to the date of the birth of their first child.<br><br> The obvious implication being that nothing about the world changed. It was your worldview that changed. And now you have to, you know, protect this fragile life—and so you are much more attuned to the dangers of the world. That&#39;s why you think there&#39;s more of them.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> You know, Julie, I have this conversation with my brother all the time, and he&#39;s always telling me his kids aren&#39;t safe. He lives in New York. He&#39;s like, “My kids aren&#39;t safe. They can&#39;t go outside. They can&#39;t go down the block.” Like, he really freaks out, you know? And: “It&#39;s way less safe than it was when we were kids.” And I&#39;m like, “Dude, we grew up in New York in the &#39;70s, right?” It was really not safe.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Like, statistically.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Statistically. And I&#39;ve shown him news articles, and I once pulled out an FBI report. I specially downloaded an FBI report that showed, you know, crime statistics in New York from when we were kids.<br><br> And his conviction is so strong about this. I can&#39;t budge him. I can&#39;t show him enough numbers or statistics to make him think, <em>Oh, things aren&#39;t worse now</em> .<br><br> I mean, Adam Mastroianni actually has a term for this. This is a little mean to my brother, but his term is <em>unearned conviction</em> . And I think what he means by that is exactly this. It&#39;s like: Your conviction is incredibly strong, even though you have really no basis to back up the story that you&#39;re attaching to that very strong conviction.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah. I mean it seems like, regardless of the FBI report, the story your brother is telling himself is super-emotionally resonant.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yes.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> And the stories that we tell ourselves about our own lives really do sort of shape who we are. It&#39;s really interesting, because when we tell these stories to ourselves about our personal lives, a lot of times those stories fall into one of two categories. One being redemptive and the other being contamination.<br><br> And so a redemptive story is like: “I have suffered through these trials and come out stronger for it, and things are looking up.” Whereas a contamination story is like: “These trials have conquered me, and I am now broken and fundamentally a worse person.”<br><br> And it probably won&#39;t surprise you to hear that contamination sequences are not great for people&#39;s mental health. That research was done with stories that we&#39;re telling about our personal lives. But it feels like we&#39;re kind of telling a contamination story about all of humanity.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> I guess what&#39;s depressing to me is: Why are those the ones that stick? I mean, there are redemption stories that are popular in American society.<br><br> But I feel like in a lot of moments in history, and now is one of them, these contamination stories—like “America was great once” or “Russia was great once”—have a particular kind of emotional juice and can really rally people.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah. I mean, maybe it&#39;s kind of like your brother&#39;s fear in New York, right? Where it&#39;s just like—that is so viscerally emotional. It&#39;s the safety of your kid. And so, of course, that&#39;s going to have like a way stronger impact.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Now Adam, did you find any appreciable differences between demographics? So if not between old and young people, what about gender differences, or people with different political ideologies?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> We didn&#39;t find any gender differences. We didn&#39;t find any differences by racial groups. We didn&#39;t find any education differences. The only other demographic difference that we found was an ideological one, a political one. The people who self-identified as more conservative perceived more decline over time than the people who self-identified as liberal.<br><br> But even for the people who were the most liberal, they still said that people are less kind today than they were 10 years ago, 20 years ago, or whatever point in the past. So this is something that conservatives said louder, but liberals said as well.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> So someone who identifies as a liberal could believe that there&#39;s less racism and sexism—but still believe that those other general universal markers of morality have declined.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yes. And in fact, it seems like they do. In our studies, the much smaller group of people who say that people are better now than they used to be—when we asked them “Why? What were you thinking of?,” one thing that does come up for them is there&#39;s more tolerance. There&#39;s less racism, sexism, ableism; all the <em>isms</em> .<br><br> So it seems like that&#39;s not what people are spontaneously thinking of when they say that people are less kind than they used to be. Because if you ask them directly, “Do you think that, for instance, people treat African Americans with more respect and courtesy or less than in the past?,” a majority of people will say more today than in the past.<br><br> But if you ask them, “Are people more or less kind today?,” they&#39;ll go less kind. So this is not what they&#39;re thinking of when they answer the question.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yeah. So it&#39;s a really, really specific feeling. I definitely think that people treat each other with more respect, largely because we have broadened the window of who is allowed to be respected, and sort of patriarchal notions of control over people&#39;s bodies and who gets to make decisions. I mean, there&#39;s so many ways in which we have opened the door to fairness and equity. I&#39;d much rather be alive today than 50 years ago, for sure.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah, I agree. And so I think it was especially surprising that I&#39;m sure there are many other people who agree. But even some of the people who do agree—they seem to think like, <em>Yeah, but that actually doesn&#39;t come from people&#39;s heart of hearts</em> . That they&#39;re actually still worse to one another now than they used to be.<br><br> Yeah; they&#39;ll say all the right things or they&#39;ll have the right opinions. But you know, they won&#39;t hold the door open for you, or they&#39;ll cheat you when they can. Now people know the right things to say, but they still <em>do</em> more of the bad things.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Do we feel the same way with people we know? Does it play out differently in our personal lives?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> You can actually also produce an illusion of improvement. You actually primarily hear good things and experience good things about people that you know. And so we thought that in your personal world, this illusion of decline might be turned down or turned off or even reversed.<br><br> And people told us: “People in general? Worse today than they were 15 years ago. People that I have known for the last 15 years? Better today than they were 15 years ago.”<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> So Julie, one thing that Adam found that I thought was so interesting was that people we know—like our own people, people we&#39;re close to or whatever—they&#39;re somehow getting better over time, and yet the general public are getting worse. I don&#39;t quite understand how those fit together.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> So I guess we just think the moral decline is happening with strangers, with all those <em>other</em> people.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Right.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> And it seems like potentially the disconnection from community that many people are experiencing could just mean that we&#39;re slotting more people into the “morally compromised, untrustworthy” category.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Right. Like, if we met more people and we had more casual acquaintances and we went to our bowling leagues or whatever, then we might include more people in that circle of people we know. And those people are good people. So that could sort of spiral upward rather than what&#39;s happening, which is a momentum downward.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Adam&#39;s study kind of seems to say that if you get to know people, then you won&#39;t think they&#39;re on a downward slope of moral depravity anymore.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> For one thing, Adam, it sounds to me like the problem is that people are absolutely certain. Like they&#39;re not questioning. Was the past a worse place? It&#39;s a sort of lack of humility. Because if you try to understand, “Well, maybe what did get worse?,” then you would come up with more specific and useful policy solutions.<br><br> I mean, I assume one reason you did this research is to point out a mistake. Like, we&#39;re all living under this delusion. And in your head—since you sound like a fairly optimistic person—is it “knowledge is power,” and people will know, and then they will stop? What&#39;s the aim, or what&#39;s your wish here?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. I mean, as a psychologist I a little bit despair of changing people&#39;s minds, because I know how difficult it is. It doesn&#39;t work the way that we think that it works, like, “Oh, you have the wrong model of the world. How about I give you the correct facts, and now you have the correct model of the world?” When does that ever happen? When has that ever happened to me? Like, never.<br><br> And one effect that I certainly hope that this has is: Whenever politicians or aspiring politicians make the claim that, you know, “Things used to be better, and put me in charge and I&#39;ll make them better again”—that&#39;s a very old thing that we&#39;ve heard many times. And it resonates with us, perhaps because we are primed to believe it, even when it&#39;s not true.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> So, Hanna, now that we know this is an illusion, right, that&#39;s very interesting. But will it actually change how you feel?<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> I don&#39;t really know. I mean, I feel like as a journalist, it depresses me a little bit because I spent a lot of time researching and marshaling facts, like I did with my brother. And to think that emotions ultimately squash all of that—I don&#39;t really know what to do with that.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> But in my own personal life, awareness is helpful. I don&#39;t think any bad can come from understanding your own emotional levers better. It&#39;s not that it immediately leads to a change, but I don&#39;t think it can ever be bad to understand, <em>Oh, I&#39;m having this emotional attachment or strong belief, and that&#39;s leading me to behave in this way.</em> That in and of itself is a small daily miracle. So that&#39;s good enough.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> <em>Listeners, if you enjoyed this conversation with Adam Mastroianni and Julie Beck, and if you generally like learning about these psychological levers that are guiding our choices, Julie hosts a full season of conversations much like this one, on the Atlantic podcast</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/how-to-build-a-happy-life/">How to Talk to People</a> . <em>You can find it wherever you listen to podcasts.</em><br><br> This episode was produced by Becca Rashid. Edited by Jocelyn Frank. Fact-checked by Isabel Cristo. Engineering by Rob Smierciak. The executive producer of audio is Claudine Ebeid. The managing editor of audio is Andrea Valdez. You can find new episodes of <em>Radio Atlantic</em> every Thursday.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2023/07/are-you-plagued-by-the-feeling-that-everyone-used-to-be-nicer/674838/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2023/07/are-you-plagued-by-the-feeling-that-everyone-used-to-be-nicer/674838/</item></channel></rss>